There are a few hopefully useful features in GNU APL:


@node    Section 2.1
@section APL Scripting

@menu
* Subsection 2.1.1::  Redirect the script file to the stdin of the GNU APL interpreter
* Subsection 2.1.2::  Make the script file executable
* Subsection 2.1.3::  How command line arguments are handled
* Subsection 2.1.4::  Helpful Features for Scripting
* Subsection 2.1.5::  Double-quoted Strings
* Subsection 2.1.6::  Multi-Line Strings
* Subsection 2.1.7::  Automatic )MORE
* Subsection 2.1.8::  Script Example
@end menu

As already mentioned, it is possible to write APL scripts. Similar to other
script languages, an APL script is a text file whose first line is a
"shebang line", i.e. a line starting with @option{#!}, followed by the
absolute path to the interpreter (in our case the GNU APL binary), followed
by command line arguments that are passed on to the interpreter. In our case
the shebang line could be, for example:

@verbatim
    #! /usr/local/bin/apl --id 1010
@end verbatim

There are essentially two ways to run an APL script: redirecting the script
file to stdin of the interpreter or making the script executable and indicate
apl as the script interpreter (followed by some command line arguments for
apl).

@node Subsection 2.1.1
@subsection Redirect the script file to the stdin of the GNU APL interpreter

A file, say SCRIPT.apl, can be redirected to apl by redirection of the shell:

@verbatim
    apl < SCRIPT.apl
@end verbatim

Alternatively, the command line option -f or -s can be used:

@verbatim
    apl -f SCRIPT.apl
    apl -s SCRIPT.apl
@end verbatim

Both ways of redirecting the file are almost identical; in the first case
redirection was performed by the shell running apl, while in the second case
the redirecting of the file was performed by apl itself.

@node Subsection 2.1.2
@subsection Make the script file executable

Alternatively the script can be made executable, specifying apl as its
interpreter (see also @option{'man 2 execve'}). For this to work, the
first line of the script must have a special format:

@verbatim
    #! /usr/local/bin/apl --script
@end verbatim

@BOP{-script} prevents: printing of a welcome banner, 
echoing of stdin to stdout, automatic loading of a )CONTINUE workspace,
and prevents starting a thread for shared variable communication.

If the path to the interpreter is relative (which might be useful if you
do not know in advance where the APL interpreter will be installed) then
it must be in $PATH of the shell that runs the script.

@node Subsection 2.1.3
@subsection How command line arguments are handled

As we have seen, GNU APL can be started directly (by entering the name
of the GNU APL binary on the command line of a shell, or indirectly by
entering the name of a script that provides the name of the GNU APL binary
on the first line of the script. In the latter case, the shell uses function
execve() to start APL, and one can provide additional arguments that are
passed on to APL. We briefly discuss both cases:

0. General Remark

There is a convention in (not only) GNU APL, that the command line options
(and possibly an optional option argument) that occur left of @BOP{-} are
options directed to (and understood by) the APL interpreter while the options
right of @BOP{-} are passed to the APL application (and their exact format is
then defined by the APL application). All command line options that were used
to start APL can later be retrieved with the system variable тОХARG in APL.

Example 1: APL started directly

We start APL with some command line options and display them with тОХARG.
The command line options for the interpreter are --silent, -l, and 37,
while the options app1 and app2 are for the APL application:

@verbatim
$ apl --silent -l 37 -- app1 app2
    тКГтОХARG
apl     
--silent
-l      
37      
--      
app1    
app2    
@end verbatim

Example 2: APL started indirectly

A script is a text file which has execute permissions. The first line
of a script, commonly known as the @b{shebang} of the script, has a
special format which specifies how the subsequent lines of the script file
shall be processed, see @b{man execve} for details.

A GNU APL script is then a script whose shebang indicates the apl binary as
the interpreter for the subsequent lines where those subsequent lines are
either APL commands or APL statements. With some limitations, executing such
an APL script yields the same result as entering the subsequent lines in
immediate execution mode.

When APL is started directly, there is only one (possibly empty) set of
command line options, which are processed by the shell and then passed
to the apl binary.

Starting APL indirectly refers to executing an APL script. In this case
there are two sets of command line options:

@itemize
@item those passed to the script as command line arguments, and
@item those on the shebang line of the script
@end itemize

When the APL script is started, possibly with command line arguments, the
command line arguments entered by the user are combined with the arguments
on the shebang line of the script in a way that is described in 'man 2 execve'.

Assume the script file SCRIPT.apl contains this (the file is shipped
with GNU APL):

@verbatim
#! /usr/local/bin/apl --id 1010 --script

      тКГтОХARG     тНЭ show command line options
      )OFF      тНЭ leave the interpreter

@end verbatim

Assume further that the script is started like this:

@verbatim
$ ./SCRIPT.apl sarg1 sarg2
@end verbatim

Then the following output, which shows the order of command line options
as seen by тОХARG, is produced:

@verbatim
   тКГтОХARG
/usr/local/bin/apl
--script          
./SCRIPT.apl      
sarg1             
sarg2 
@end verbatim

This suggests that the options and option arguments are constructed by execve()
(the function that is eventually responsible for processing scripts in shells
and other executables) in the following order:

1. Interpreter name (the first name in the shebang, here: /usr/local/bin/apl)

2. Optional Interpreter arguments (here: --script)

3. Script filename (here: ./SCRIPT.apl)

4. Script arguments (here: sarg1 sarg2)

CAUTION: as discussed in 'man 2 execve' the interpretation of the optional
interpreter arguments (2. above) is system specific and possibly not portable.
For that reason the optional interpreter argument should not be missing (you
can use -- to provide at least one argument) and also not more than one
argument. On GNU/Linux systems the following shebang lines of the script are
understood:

@verbatim
/usr/local/bin/apl
/usr/local/bin/apl --
/usr/local/bin/apl -s
/usr/local/bin/apl --script
/usr/local/bin/apl -s --
/usr/local/bin/apl --script --
@end verbatim

The recommended form is: @verb{|/usr/local/bin/apl --script|}.

Note that @BOP{-} and any options that follow it on the shebang line
MAY OR MAY NOT be included in тОХARG (this depends on the platform used).
In contrast, options that follow @BOP{-} on the script command line
WILL BE shown since this is controlled by GNU APL and not by the platform.
There is normally no point in passing any application options on the shebang
line to APL because such parameters can more easily be provided directly
further down in the script. However, in cases where the script has only
application options it may be convenient to make @b{@verb{|--|}} the last
option of the shebang so that the user of the script need not specify it
manually.

Using @BOP{-} on the shebang line of the script file usually prevents
subsequent options on the shebang line from being interpreted as APL options
(and, more importantly, from causing @b{unknown option} errors when GNU APL
starts). At least under GNU/Linux with @b{bash} the subsequent options will
be passed to the APL application via тОХARG.

Depending on this exact behavior cannot be recommended. A cleaner approach
is to use options starting with - or @BOP{-} only for the interpreter
options, and options starting with + for application options. This should
work on all platforms because for strings, say, APLOPT, ARG1, ARG2, ...,
which contain no whitespace:

@itemize
@item @b{+APLOPT} is ignored, although shown in тОХARG,
@item @b{++APLOPT ARG1} is ignored, although shown in тОХARG,
@item @b{+++APLOPT ARG1 ARG2} is ignored, although shown in тОХARG,
@item @b{...}
@end itemize

@node Subsection 2.1.4
@subsection Helpful Features for Scripting

GNU APL provides three system variables and functions that are particularly
useful for scripting:

@itemize
@item тОХARG: access to the command line arguments given to the interpreter,
@item тОХENV: access to the environment variables of the process running the
        interpreter, and
@item тОХINP: Here-Document-alike function for creating large text variables
@end itemize

@subsubsection тОХARG

The system variable тОХARG contains all command line arguments passed to the
interpreter. In the initial example above this would be a nested 3-element
vector:

@verbatim
    /usr/local/bin/apl --id 1010
@end verbatim

@subsubsection тОХENV

There are usually at least two ways of passing parameters to a script:

@itemize
@item as command line options, and/or
@item by means of environment variables
@end itemize

Just as the system variable тОХARG makes the command line options used
available to APL, so does the system function тОХENV make the environment
variables available to APL. Since there normally exist far more
environment variables than command line options, тОХENV is a monadic function
whose argument is a filter for the name(s) of the variable(s) to be retrieved.

тОХENV B returns all environment variables whose name starts with B.
If тН┤B is 0, like:

@verbatim
    тОХENV ''
@end verbatim

then @b{all} environment variables of the process running GNU APL are
returned.

The result of тОХENV is a (possibly empty) N├Ч2 matrix. The first column
contains the name(s) of the environment variable(s), while the second
column contains their value(s). The name and the value are both strings.

The number N of environment variables returned by тОХENV obviously depends on
the number of environment variables whose name begins with the prefix
given in B; shorter prefixes B therefore result in higher counts N. B is case
sensitive; by convention the names of environment variables are all uppercase.
Note the subtle difference between shell variables and environment variables
in shells like @b{bash}: тОХENV returns only environment variables (which
are set with command @b{setenv} in bash), but not shell variables (which
are set with command @b{set} in bash). For a shell variable to occur
in тОХENV it must be @b{export}ed into the environment of the process
before the GNU APL interpreter is started.

@subsubsection тОХINP

If you need to create a longer static text, like the body of a web page,
then you would normally construct it in APL like this:

@verbatim
BODY тЖР тКВ 'First line'
BODY тЖР BODY , тКВ 'Second line'
BODY тЖР BODY , тКВ 'Third line'
   ...
@end verbatim

The above is obviously not very handy for longer texts. Instead you may
write the following in a GNU APL script:

@verbatim
BODYтЖРтОХINP 'END-OF-тОХINP'
First line
Second line
Third line
   ...
END-OF-тОХINP
@end verbatim

This works like "Here documents" in @b{bash}. The right argument of тОХINP is
the end of text marker.

тОХINP also has a dyadic form where the left argument specifies an escape
sequence from text to APL and back to the text, similar to PHP scripts.
For example:

@verbatim
ZтЖР'<?apl' '?>' тОХINP 'END-OF-тОХINP'
First line
Time is now: <?apl тНХтОХTS ?>
Third line
...
END-OF-тОХINP
@end verbatim

This creates a mainly static text with a small dynamic plug-in computed by
APL:

@verbatim
      тКГZ
First line                       
Time is now: 2022 8 4 15 15 2 177
Third line                       
...         
@end verbatim

It should be noted that, while тОХINP simplifies the construction of multi-line
strings compared to standard APL, it has come of age and these days an even
simpler feature - Multi-line strings as described below - is provided for the
same purpose. The monadic тОХINP has therefore become obsolete.

@node Subsection 2.1.5
@subsection Double-quoted Strings

Standard APL literals (aka. strings) such as 'Hello' are single quoted. As a
matter of convenience, GNU APL also provides double-quoted strings which
differ from single quoted strings in two ways:

@itemize

@item A standard single quoted APL string is a vector if its length тЙа 1 but
a scalar if its length = 1. This is sometimes inconvenient and therefore
double-quoted strings are more consistent in always being vectors regardless
of their length. In other words, 'A' is a scalar while "A" is a vector.

@item Double-quoted strings understand the standard C escape sequences
for control character, such as \n for ASCII line feed, \t for ASCII TAB, etc.

@end itemize

@node Subsection 2.1.6
@subsection Multi-Line Strings

A substantial disadvantage of тОХINP is that it only works in immediate
execution mode (and consequently also in .apl scripts), but not the bodies of
defined functions. Multi-line strings fill this gap for string literals that
span several lines of text @b{inside} the body of defined functions.
Multi-Line strings have become more and more advanced (and elegant) over time.
For this reason they currently come in different flavors (of which the older
ones will eventually disappear).

@subsubsection Old-style Multi-Line Strings

Old-style multi-line strings were the first attempt to provide long strings
for defined functions. The idea for the old-style multi-line strings was
adopted from shells like @b{bash} where, for example,

@verbatim
echo "Line1
   Line2"
@end verbatim

prints:

@verbatim
Line1
   Line2
@end verbatim

In simple terms this means that as long as the number of " characters is
odd, the string remains open until the closing " is found (which makes
the number even again).

Old-style multi-line strings are not allowed in immediate execution mode
because they could easily be entered by mistake (by simply forgetting the
terminating " or ' of a standard string) and that would have obscured the
familiar behavior of immediate execution mode. In function definition
mode, the total number of function lines is known and it can therefore
check if a multi-line string inside the function is properly terminated.
Immediate execution mode, however, is open-ended and therefore a forgotten
closing " can lead to a fatal misinterpretation of (intended) string
content as (unintended) APL code, with lots of nonsense error messages.

Like in @b{bash} and also other shells, an old-style multi-line string starts
at the last " on a line of a defined function that has an
@b{an odd number of " characters}. The string continues over the subsequent
function lines until the next " is found. The result is a nested
APL value containing one nested string per line involved.

In immediate execution mode an old-style multi-line string yields, like
in standard APL:

@verbatim
No string end found+
@end verbatim

For example:
@verbatim

тИЗZтЖРFOO
 ZтЖР"ABC
 DEF
 GHIJK"
тИЗ

4 тОХCR FOO
тФПтЖТтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФУ
тФГтФПтЖТтФБтФБтФУ тФПтЖТтФБтФБтФБтФУ тФПтЖТтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФУтФГ
тФГтФГABCтФГ тФГ DEFтФГ тФГ GHIJKтФГтФГ
тФГтФЧтФБтФБтФБтФЫ тФЧтФБтФБтФБтФБтФЫ тФЧтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФЫтФГ
тФЧтИКтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФЫ
@end verbatim

If the first string is empty then the nested value starts with an empty
string, but completely empty lines in defined functions are ignored:

@verbatim
тИЗZтЖРFOO
 ZтЖР"
ABC
 DEF

  GHIJK"
тИЗ

4 тОХCR FOO
тФПтЖТтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФУ
тФГтФПтКЦтФУ тФПтЖТтФБтФБтФУ тФПтЖТтФБтФБтФБтФУ тФПтЖТтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФУтФГ
тФГтФГ тФГ тФГABCтФГ тФГ DEFтФГ тФГ  GHIJKтФГтФГ
тФГтФЧтФБтФЫ тФЧтФБтФБтФБтФЫ тФЧтФБтФБтФБтФБтФЫ тФЧтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФЫтФГ
тФЧтИКтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФЫ
@end verbatim

@subsubsection New-style Multi-Line Strings

The combination of @b{тОХINP} for immediate execution mode and multi-line
strings for defined functions achieved, at least in principle, the goal of
specifying large amounts of text in a simpler manner than in standard APL.
However, having different methods for creating multi-line string literals
in different APL modes could not convince entirely.

The search for a more intuitive and more consistent solution then led to
new-style multi-line strings. These strings adopted the triple quote (""")
syntax known from e.g. the Python language. The syntax of new-style
multi-line strings is cleaner: empty lines are handled more consistently and
the string lines are completely separated from the APL code lines.
More importantly, new-style multi-line strings work alike in immediate
execution mode, in scripts, and in defined functions. New-style strings are a
little different and syntactically stricter than their old-style companions:

@itemize
@item the starting """ must be placed at the end of an APL code line, i.e.
there is no more mixing of APL code and string content on the same line.
An old-style string starts with APL code and ends with the first line of
the string, while a new-style string starts with an APL code line and
the string itself begins at the following line.

@item the ending """ must be placed at the end of a separate line with only
spaces allowed before the """ (to horizontally indent-align it with the
leading """ if so  desired). In old-style strings the text up to the
termination " is part of the string while in new-style strings it is not.

@item Neither the starting nor the ending line become nested strings of the
result, and every line can be clearly identified as being either APL code or
else string text.
@end itemize

Example:
@verbatim
 4 тОХCR """
ABC
 DEF

  GHIJK
       """
тФПтЖТтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФУ
тФГтФПтЖТтФБтФБтФУ тФПтЖТтФБтФБтФБтФУ тФПтКЦтФУ тФПтЖТтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФУтФГ
тФГтФГABCтФГ тФГ DEFтФГ тФГ тФГ тФГ  GHIJKтФГтФГ
тФГтФЧтФБтФБтФБтФЫ тФЧтФБтФБтФБтФБтФЫ тФЧтФБтФЫ тФЧтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФЫтФГ
тФЧтИКтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФЫ
@end verbatim

When entering new-style multi-line strings, the prompt is prefixed by тЖТ to
indicate that a Multi-Line String is being entered.

тОХINP and old-style strings will coexist for a while, but may eventually
disappear at some point in time.

@subsubsection ┬л ┬╗ Strings

When new-style multi-line strings are used in scripts the related error
reporting (if the syntax is used incorrectly) can become cumbersome. For
example, if one forgets the closing """ of a multi-line string then the next
""" (which was meant as the start of a new multi-line string) is mistaken as
the (forgotten) end of the previous one. The often long content of
the new string is then parsed as APL code and will usually produce many
error messages, all of them nonsense. Things get worse if the script itself
is long because the odd/even nature of the quotes will then persist until
the end of the string (or at least until the next forgotten quote, if any).

To deal with this problem, GNU APL also allows strings whose contents are
enclosed in double angle quotation marks ┬л and ┬╗. In inline strings '...'
and "...", as well as in multi-line strings """ ... """, there is no general
(and reliable) way to decide if a user has forgotten the ending quote(s),
which leads to the problems above.

For this reason, GNU APL now also allows inline and multi-line strings
like, for example:

@verbatim
      ┬лHello world┬╗
Hello world

      8 тОХCR ┬л┬л┬л
тЖТ      Line 1
тЖТ        Line 2
тЖТ      ┬╗┬╗┬╗
тФМтЖТтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФР
тФВтФМтЖТтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФР тФМтЖТтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФРтФВ
тФВтФВLine 1тФВ тФВ  Line 2тФВтФВ
тФВтФФтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФШ тФФтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФШтФВ
тФФ╧╡тФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФШ

      тНЭ provoke an error...
      8 тОХCR ┬л┬л┬л
тЖТ      Line 1
тЖТ        Line 2
тЖТ      ┬л┬л┬л
*** WARNING: see (second) ┬л┬л┬л when expecting the closing ┬╗┬╗┬╗
тФМтЖТтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФР
тФВтФМтЖТтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФР тФМтЖТтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФРтФВ
тФВтФВLine 1тФВ тФВ  Line 2тФВтФВ
тФВтФФтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФШ тФФтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФШтФВ
тФФ╧╡тФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФШ

@end verbatim

Another advantage of ┬л┬л┬л ... ┬╗┬╗┬╗ over """ ... """ is that a decent text
editor (read: vi/vim) may jump back and forth between the corresponding
opening ┬л and closing ┬╗ with a single key stroke (character % in vi/vim).
For this to work, add the following line to /etc/vim/vimrc (or ~/.vimrc):

@verbatim
set matchpairs+=┬л:┬╗
@end verbatim

@node Subsection 2.1.7
@subsection Automatic )MORE

The GNU APL command )MORE provides, in some cases, additional information
about a prior APL error. The availability of such additional information
is indicated by a + at the end of the error message. The additional
information is automatically discarded when the next non-empty line
is entered. For example:

@verbatim
      "ABC"[4]
INDEX ERROR+
      'ABC'[4]
      ^    ^
      )MORE
min index=тОХIO (=1), offending index=4, max index=тОХIO+2 (=3)
      тЧК тНЭ clears )MORE

      )MORE
NO )MORE ERROR INFO

@end verbatim

This is rather useful in purely interactive mode where the user can issue
the )MORE command directly after an APL error has occurred to help figure
out what exactly went wrong. In a script, however, the standard )MORE command
(as inherited from IBM APL2) is fairly useless for two reasons:

@itemize
@item A human user has a chance to issue the )MORE command interactively
after an error has occurred, while a script continues after displaying the
error message, and
@item It is rather difficult to predict where the next errors will occur,
i.e. where to place the )MORE command in the script.
@end itemize

To make the )MORE command more useful for scripts, in GNU APL it can be
augmented with an optional argument AUTO like this:

@verbatim
      )MORE AUTO ON
Automatic )MORE is now: ON
      
      "ABC"[4]
min index=тОХIO (=1), offending index=4, max index=тОХIO+2 (=3)
INDEX ERROR+
      'ABC'[4]
      ^    ^
@end verbatim

If ON/OFF is omitted then the automatic )MORE mode is toggled. The additional
)MORE information is displayed before the standard 3-line APL error message.

@node Subsection 2.1.8
@subsection Script Example

Note that the two different ways of running an APL script have an impact on
how тОХARG looks like. If stdin is redirected then there is only one (possibly
empty) set of command line options. Otherwise there are two sets of command
line options: command line options for the apl interpreter and command line
options for the script.

Consider the following simple script called SCRIPT.apl in directory workspaces:

@verbatim
#! /usr/local/bin/apl --script

тКГтОХARG   тНЭ show command line options
)OFF    тНЭ leave the interpreter
@end verbatim

If SCRIPT.apl is redirected to stdin of the APL interpreter:

@verbatim
 /usr/local/bin/apl --silent <  ../workspaces/SCRIPT.apl

 or

 /usr/local/bin/apl --silent -f ../workspaces/SCRIPT.apl
@end verbatim

then the first line @option{#! /usr/local/bin/apl --script} of file SCRIPT.apl 
is merely a comment (GNU APL accepts both the traditional APL character
тНЭ and the character # as start of a comment). The @BOP{-script} option
is therefore ignored and the following mix of input and output is
shown on the screen. The input from the script is indented by the
usual APL prompt of 6 blanks, while the output of the APL interpreter
is not indented.

@verbatim
      #! /usr/local/bin/apl --script
      
      тКГтОХARG     тНЭ show command line options
      )OFF      тНЭ leave the interpreter

@end verbatim

If we run the same script directly:

@verbatim
../workspaces/SCRIPT.apl
@end verbatim

Then we get:

@verbatim

 /usr/local/bin/apl --script ../workspaces/SCRIPT.apl 

@end verbatim

The @BOP{-script} implies @BOP{-noCIN} so that the
input lines for the interpreter are no longer echoed to the output.
This is most likely what you want when writing a script.

Also, the first line of the script is no longer ignored as a comment,
but controls the command line argument (and thus тОХARG) of the interpreter.
The additional command line argument @option{../workspaces/SCRIPT.apl}
comes from function execve (see 'man 2 execve').

If we provide an argument, say SCRIPTARG, to SCRIPT.apl:

@verbatim
../workspaces/SCRIPT.apl SCRIPTARG
@end verbatim

then it shows up at the end of тОХARG:

@verbatim

 /usr/local/bin/apl --script ../workspaces/SCRIPT.apl SCRIPTARG 

@end verbatim

A final note on scripting in GNU APL is that the тИЗ-editor works slightly
differently when it is used in a script. If a user edits an APL function
interactively then an attempt to open an existing function with a full
header gives a DEFN ERROR:

@verbatim

      тИЗZтЖРFOO B
[1] тИЗ
      
            тИЗZтЖРFOO B
DEFN ERROR+
      тИЗZтЖРFOO B
             ^
      )MORE
attempt to тИЗ-open existing function with new function header

@end verbatim

In contrast to a user who can react to the DEFN ERROR, a script cannot detect
this situation and would continue to push lines (which were intended to be
the body of the defined function) into the APL interpreter. That would most
likely cause fairly undesirable behavior. For example, if the lines of a
defined function start with line numbers (like [1], [2], ...) then every
such line would give a SYNTAX ERROR, and other errors can be expected as
well.

For that reason, if the тИЗ-editor is used in a script and attempts to redefine
an existing defined function then the existing function is simply overwritten
with the new one and no DEFN ERROR is raised.


@node    Section 2.2
@section Axis argument in defined functions

Defined functions and operators (including lambdas) accept an axis argument.
For example:

@verbatim

тИЗZтЖРAverage[X] B
 ZтЖР(+/[X]B) ├╖ (тН┤B)[X]
тИЗ

      Average[1] 5 5тН┤тН│25
11 12 13 14 15

      Average[2] 5 5тН┤тН│25
3 8 13 18 23

@end verbatim

Syntactically, the axis is used in the same way as for primitive functions
and operators.

There are no constraints on the axis such as being integers. Therefore you
can use an axis as a third function argument. Keep in mind, however, that
doing so will make your APL code incompatible with other APL interpreters.
Use this feature carefully!


@node    Section 2.3
@section Colored Output

The APL interpreter gets its input from the standard input (stdin),
which is normally connected to the user's keyboard,
but can also be a file if APL scripting, the @BOP{f} option,
or the @BOP{T} option is used.

The APL interpreter prints its results on either the standard output (stdout)
for normal APL output, or to the error output (stderr) for additional
trouble-shooting information.

You can print the 3 channels stdin, stdout, and stderr in different colors
by means of the debug command ]XTERM. Command ]XTERM ON enables colored
output while ]XTERM OFF disables it (for example to avoid annoying ANSI
Escape sequences when forwarding stdout or stderr to a file).

Default colored output assumes a terminal (-emulation) that understands
ANSI (or VT100) Escape sequences. The xterm that comes with most recent
GNU/Linux distributions is a perfect choice supporting both colors and
UTF-8 (Unicode) encoded character I/O.

Non-ANSI terminals, as well as other colors than the default ones, can be
configured in the 'preferences' file. The 'preferences' file also
contains a description of all possible color settings.


@node    Section 2.4
@section Comparison Rules

Both IBM APL2 and the ISO standard require that the arguments of <, тЙд, тЙе,
and > (but not of = or тЙа) are integer or real numbers. As a consequence,
the argument(s) of тНЛ or тНТ (which require comparison) must also be a vector
of integer or real numbers.

In contrast, GNU APL also allows the comparison of characters and numbers or
the comparison of complex numbers according to the following, more general,
rules.

Let A and B be two APL values to be compared. The final result of comparing
A and B is the first verdict (i.e. either A < B, or A > B, or A = B)
obtained when following the rules below in the indicated order:

@enumerate
@item
Comparison by rank: if (тН┤тН┤A) < (тН┤тН┤B) then A < B and vice versa.

@item
Comparison by shape: if (тН┤A) < (тН┤B) then A < B and vice versa. The
first differing shape item (from the left) decides.

@item
Comparison of ravel elements: at this point (тН┤A) тЙб (тН┤B). If all
corresponding ravel elements of A and B are equal (i.e. tolerantly equal
within тОХCT as defined in the ISO standard) then A = B.

Otherwise let A1 and B1 be the first corresponding ravel elements of A and B
with A1 тЙа B1. If A1 < B1 then A < B and vice versa. The comparison A1 < B1
is made according to the following rules 4 - 8 below.

@item
Comparison by depth:

@itemize
@item
If A1 and B1 are both nested: the rules 1 - 3 above are (recursively)
applied to corresponding ravel elements of тКГA1 and тКГB1 until a verdict is
obtained.

@item if A1 is simple and B1 is nested then A < B and vice versa.

@item
otherwise (i.e. A1 and B1 are both simple): A < B if A1 < B1 according to
rules 5 - 8 below and vice versa.
@end itemize

@item
Comparison by Unicode: if A1 and B1 are both character values and
(тОХUCS A1) < (тОХUCS B1) then A < B and vice versa.

@item
Comparison by type: If A1 is a character and B1 is numeric, then A < B
and vice versa.

@item
Comparison by numeric value: if A1 and B1 are both numeric values then:

@itemize
@item
Comparison by real part: if (9тЧЛA1) < (9тЧЛB1) then A < B and vice versa.

@item
Comparison by imaginary part: otherwise if (11тЧЛA1) < (11тЧЛB1) then A < B
and vice versa.
@end itemize

@item
Otherwise: A = B.
@end enumerate

Another way of describing the rules above is that the comparison of two values
is comprised of sub-comparisons of certain properties of the values in the
following order:

@itemize
@item the ranks of the values,
@item the shapes of the values,
@item the first differing ravel element (in row-major order) of the values,
@item the depths of the differing ravel elements,
@item the types (character vs. numeric) of the differing ravel elements,
@item the Unicodes of the differing ravel elements (if applicable)
@item the real parts of numeric values,
@item the imaginary parts of numeric values,
@end itemize

Note: Rules 1 and 2 above are only relevant for comparisons made in the
context of sorting (i.e. for тНЛ or тНТ). This is because for =, тЙа, <, тЙд, тЙе,
or > either a RANK ERROR or a LENGTH ERROR is raised if the ranks or shapes
of A and B do not match:

@verbatim
      (9 8) < (1 2 3)
LENGTH ERROR
      9 8<1 2 3
      ^  ^

      тНЛ(9 8) (1 2 3)
1 2
@end verbatim

The reason for comparing complex numbers first by their real parts and then
by their imaginary part and not, for example, first by their magnitude and
then by their angle is that the chosen order gives more consistent results
when comparing near-complex numbers or their true real companions. For
example, a magnitude first comparison of complex numbers would make
┬п2 < ┬п1 < ┬п2J1E┬п20 for the near-complex number ┬п2J1E┬п20.

@b{CAUTION}: The comparison of two strings (i.e. nested character
vectors) may give unexpected results because shorter strings come before
longer strings. For example, 'Zoo' comes @b{before} 'Adam' even
though one might expect the opposite.

@verbatim
      Z[тНЛZ тЖР 'Adam' 'Zoo']
 Zoo Adam 

      Z[тНЛZ тЖР 'Adam' 'Zora']
 Adam Zora
@end verbatim

This pitfall can be avoided by enforcing the same length for all strings
being compared or sorted. A simple way to achieve that is the use of
@b{тКВ[2]тКГ} like this (assuming тОХIOтЖР1):

@verbatim
      Z[тНЛZ тЖР тКВ[2]тКГ 'Adam' 'Zoo']
 Adam Zoo  

      Z[тНЛZ тЖР тКВ[2]тКГ 'Adam' 'Zora']
 Adam Zora
@end verbatim


@node    Section 2.5
@section Complex Numbers

Complex numbers are fully supported.


@node    Section 2.6
@section Debug Commands

In addition to the classical APL commands like )LOAD or )SAVE, GNU APL
has a number of debug commands for debugging purposes.
Regular APL commands start with ) and print their output on stdout.
Debug commands start with ] and print their output on stderr. Normally
you cannot easily distinguish between stdout and stderr, but another
GNU APL feature, colored output, uses different colors for stdout and stderr.

Type )HELP or ]HELP in the interpreter for a list of all commands available.


@node    Section 2.7
@section Direct Functions (Lambdas)

GNU APL supports direct functions (aka. lambdas), but only in a rather
limited form.

@subsection Named Lambdas

A statement of the form

@verbatim
      FUN тЖР { body_statement } 
@end verbatim

creates a named lambda. A body_statement can contain variable names тН║ and тН╡
as well as function names тН╢ and тН╣ which are replaced by the actual arguments
of the lambda. If both тН║ and тН╡ are present in body_statement then the lambda
is dyadic. If only тН╡ is present then it is monadic, and if neither тН║ nor тН╡ is
present then the lambda is niladic.

Likewise, if тН╢ and тН╣ are present then the lambda is a dyadic operator. If only
тН╢ is present then it is a monadic operator, and if neither тН╢ nor тН╣ is present
then the lambda is a normal function.

GNU APL supports an axis argument in normal user defined functions and
operators. In lambda expressions the Greek letter ╧З (Chi) is the variable
name for an axis argument.

The way a named lambda is implemented in GNU APL is that the expression

@verbatim
      FUN тЖР { body_expression }
@end verbatim

is translated to a two-line function тОХFX 'lambda_header' 'body_expression'.

For example:

@verbatim
      )FNS

      SUM тЖР { тН║ + тН╡ }

      )FNS
SUM

      тИЗSUM[тОХ]тИЗ
[0] ╬╗тЖРтН║ SUM тН╡
[1] ╬╗тЖР тН║ + тН╡ 

@end verbatim

The lambda_header is automatically deduced from the presence or absence
of the variable names (тН║, тН╡, and ╧З) and function names (тН╢ and тН╣) in the
body_expression and from whether the body_expression is empty (no ╬╗тЖР) or
not (with ╬╗тЖР).

It is possible to specify local variables that work exactly like their
companions in normal defined functions. Please note that this is different
from some other APL interpreters which treat all variables in lambda bodies
as local variables. The syntax for specifying local variables is the same
as for the header in normal defined functions: they are added at the end
with semicolons as separators. In the above example one could add local
variables C and D like this:

@verbatim
      SUM тЖР { тН║ + тН╡ ;C;D }

      тОХCR 'SUM'
╬╗тЖРтН║ ╬╗1 тН╡;C;D 
╬╗тЖР тН║ + тН╡     

@end verbatim

If a named lambda is created inside a function, then the name of the lambda
(i.e. the name left of тЖР @{ ... @}) can be made a local variable of the
function in which the named lambda is created. This creates a lambda with
local scope.

Please note that the above only describes the current implementation of named
lambda in GNU APL. A consequence of that implementation is that the symbols
тН║, тН╡, ╧З, тН╢, тН╣, and ╬╗ are pretty much behaving like user defined variables. In
particular, they can be used outside named or unnamed lambdas. However, that
may change in the future and therefore such use of тН║, тН╡, ╧З, тН╢, тН╣, and ╬╗ outside
is certainly a bad idea.

@subsection Unnamed Lambdas

An unnamed lambda is an expression inside @{ @} but without assigning it to a
name. This is often used together with the EACH operator.
For example:

@verbatim

      { тН┤ , тН╡ } ┬и 'a' 'ab' 'abc'
 1  2  3 

@end verbatim

Unnamed lambdas are automatically local in scope (similar to labels). They can
be passed as function arguments to operators. However, unnamed lambdas are NOT
inserted into the symbol table of the interpreter. They are therefore not
visible to functions like тОХCR or by the тИЗ-editor. Occasionally the names ╬╗1,
╬╗2, ... may show up in commands like )SIS. These names are automatically
generated for unnamed lambdas in order to provide a name in places where a
function name is needed.

@subsection Limitations of Lambdas

There are a number of features related to lambdas that are present in other
APL interpreters but that are NOT implemented in GNU APL. This includes
multiple statements, guards, lexical scoping, and probably more.


@node    Section 2.8
@section ]DOXY Command

A particularly useful debug command is ]DOXY. It dumps the current workspace
in brows-able HTML format with listings of defined functions and hyperlinks
between them.

@smallexample
]DOXY                   тНЭ write documentation to /tmp/WSNAME/*
]DOXY dest              тНЭ write documentation to dest/WSNAME/*
@end smallexample

The starting point for browsing the documentation are the files:

@smallexample
/tmp/WSNAME/index.html         тНЭ for ]DOXY without arguments, or
dest/WSNAME/index.html         тНЭ for e.g. ]DOXY dest
@end smallexample

The index.html files above usually correspond to the following URIs in your
browser:

@smallexample
file:///tmp/WSNAME or
file:///absolute-path-to-dest/WSNAME respectively.
@end smallexample

In the above examples WSNAME is the )WSID of the workspace in which the ]DOXY
command was executed.

One can (and should make it a habit to) insert special comments into defined
functions which are copied into proper places inside the documentation that is
generated by the ]DOXY command. These "doxy" comments begin with тНЭтНЭ (as opposed
to "normal" APL comments that start with a single тНЭ. Doxy comments are
typically one-liners that briefly explain what a function is supposed to do.

For example:

@verbatim
тИЗZтЖРA SUM B
 тНЭтНЭ Return the sum of A and B          тЖР ]DOXY comment:  (double тНЭ)
 тНЭ  A: numeric                         тЖР "normal" APL comments (single тНЭ) ...
 тНЭ  B: numeric
 ZтЖРA + B
тИЗ
@end verbatim

But please @b{note the following}: in the original @b{doxygen} program
(for C, C++, or other languages) source code lines may be a mix of code
and comments (including doxygen comments). In the @b{]DOXY} command of GNU
APL a line of a defined function shall be either APL code or else a doxygen
comment (i.e. starting with тНЭтНЭ). Doxygen comments indented with blanks are
allowed (for the sake of readability).

Since a doxygen comment is also a valid APL comment, it is perfectly legal
to put a doxygen comment at the end of a line that starts with APL code.
However, such lines will be ignored by the @b{]DOXY} command.

The parser generates no extra code from the doxygen comments, and therefore
the use of many doxygen comments causes no performance problem (and neither
do regular APL comments).


@node    Section 2.9
@section Commands )COPY_ONCE, )DUMP, and DUMP-HTML

In standard APL, workspaces are processed with the standard commands )LOAD,
)COPY, and )SAVE. GNU APL provides additional commands to process workspaces.

@subsection )DUMP Command

GNU APL has a command )DUMP that saves a workspace to disk, similar to the
)OUT command. The difference between them is the file format being produced.
While )OUT produces a file in IBM's workspace interchange format (aka. an
.atf file), )DUMP produces a file in GNU APL's script format (i.e. readable
APL statements). Files written with )DUMP can be edited with normal text
editors (vi, Emacs), read back with "apl -f", or made executable (see
scripting).

@subsection )DUMP-HTML Command

The )DUMP-HTML command is similar to the )DUMP command and the output format
is similar as well. The difference is that those characters that need
HTML-escaping (e.g. '<' becomes &lt; and '>' becomes '&gt; etc.) are
HTML-escaped. The output of the )DUMP-HTML command can therefore be directly
used by a web browser to display workspace listings (to share the code).

The files written with the )DUMP-HTML command have the extension @b{.html}.

In addition to the APL code, the .html files produced have a short HTML
<head> section template. The user should replace the fields marked
with @b{??????} with proper values (for the author, the copyright owner,
and a short description) before publishing the page.

@subsection )COPY_ONCE Command

Command )COPY_ONCE copies all objects (variables, functions and operators)
from some other workspace into the current workspace similar to )COPY.
However, )COPY_ONCE does this only once; a second invocation of
)COPY_ONCE with the same workspace (and the same library reference number)
is silently ignored. This speeds up the )COPYing of libraries that occur
in several )DUMP-ed or )SAVE-ed workspaces.


@node    Section 2.10
@section ]NEXTFILE and ]PUSHFILE Commands

@subsection ]NEXTFILE

The debug command ]NEXTFILE, when used in an APL script file, terminates
the processing of that file and continues processing in the next script file
(if any) or else enters immediate execution mode. Unlike )OFF (which terminates
the interpreter), ]NEXTFILE does not terminate the interpreter but only changes
its input source to the next script file (if there is one remaining) and enters
immediate execution only if all scripts were processed.

The user may, for example, want to use the space near the end of the script
to add longer comments (as to what the script does, how it works, how it is
used, etc.) without the need to prepend every line with тНЭ or #.

For example:

@verbatim
#!/usr/local/bin/apl

тНЭ see documentation at the end of this file

<APL CODE...>

]NEXTFILE

This workspace does the following...

@end verbatim


@subsection ]PUSHFILE

The debug command ]PUSHFILE is similar to ]NEXTFILE in that it terminates
the processing of the current script file. Unlike ]NEXTFILE, ]PUSHFILE does
not proceed to the next script file but enters a new immediate execution
context in which the user can interact with the interpreter. This context
processes user input until a ]NEXTFILE command is given. After a ]NEXTFILE
command, the immediate execution context processing proceeds at the next
line after the ]PUSHFILE command.


@node    Section 2.11
@section History and TAB completion

Until GNU APL 1.4 / SVN 465, GNU APL used libreadline for interactive user
input. libreadline did provide two useful features: tab expansion (the tab
key would expand file names) and history (the cursor up/down keys would recall
previously entered lines).

Since SVN 465 libreadline was removed and the standard TAB expansion and
history of libreadline were replaced by more context sensitive (i.e. APL
aware) implementations:

1. Instead of simply recalling the last line entered by the user, there are
now different histories for different input contexts:

1a. The input history in immediate execution recalls the last line entered
in immediate execution (and not, for example, lines entered in function
editing mode or тНЮ input.

1b. Likewise, тНЮ recalls the last line entered for тНЮ-input

1c. тОХ recalls the last line entered for тОХ-input

1d. In the тИЗ-editor, the other function lines of the function being edited
can be recalled. This is far more handy than the тИЗ-editor commands for
recalling function lines (which are not fully supported in GNU APL).

2. Instead of always TAB-completing file names, the tab character now
understands different TAB-completion contexts:

2a. Input starting with . or / is completed as a filename like readline did.

2b. Input starting with ) or ] is completed as command-name name or, to some
extent, as command arguments.

2c. Input starting with тОХ is completed as a system function name or a
system variable name.

2d. Input starting with letters, тИЖ, or тНЩ is completed as a user defined
function or variable name.


@node    Section 2.12
@section Logging Facilities

The APL interpreter has over 30 logging facilities. Each logging facility
can be ON (and then produces some logging output on stderr) or OFF. The
decision which logging facility shall be ON and which shall be OFF can be
made at compile time (of the APL interpreter) or at run-time. 

If the decision is made at compile time - we call that static logging - then
it cannot be changed later on. Otherwise - we call that dynamic logging -
there is a debug command ]LOG that allows logging facilities to be turned
ON or OFF.

@subsection Static Logging

By default the logging facilities that shall be turned ON are defined
statically. To change the logging facilities that shall be turned ON,
you can edit the file src/Logging.def which defines the different logging
facilities. The first argument of macro log_def() specifies that the
indicated logging facility shall be ON (1) or OFF (0).

Static logging results in a faster interpreter than dynamic logging because
the decision to log something is made at compile time and not at run-time.

If you benchmark the APL interpreter, then ./configure Static Logging by
NOT setting DYNAMIC_LOG_WANTED=yes.

@subsection Dynamic Logging

Dynamic Logging is intended for trouble-shooters of GNU APL, but also for
those who are interested in the internals of GNU APL. Dynamic Logging is
enabled by setting DYNAMIC_LOG_WANTED=yes when running ./configure.

If Dynamic Logging is enabled, then the already mentioned file
src/Logging.def determines the initial setting of each logging facility.

The command

 ]LOG

(without arguments) then shows all logging facilities and their current
state. The command

]LOG N

toggles the state of logging facility N from OFF to ON and back.


@node    Section 2.13
@section Rational Numbers

GNU APL has limited support for rational numbers. Instead of dividing integers
(and possibly causing rounding errors), integer quotients are kept undivided
internally until some function requires a conversion to a floating point
(double) value.

Currently only +, -, ├Ч, and ├╖ preserve rational numbers where possible, but
this list may grow in the future. Monadic + (a no-op for non-complex numbers)
explicitly converts rational numbers to floating point numbers.

A quotient is internally stored as a 64-bit numerator and a 64-bit denominator.
In some cases arithmetic with rational numbers is faster than with doubles, but
in most cases it is slower.

For that reason support for rational numbers is disabled by default and must
be enabled via ./configure (see README-2-configure).


@node    Section 2.14
@section Hex Numbers

GNU APL supports sedecimal numbers. They start with $ and can be uppercase or
lowercase:

@verbatim
      $2a
42

      $2A
42
@end verbatim


@node    Section 2.15
@section User-defined Commands

There is a simple mechanism to define additional APL commands. This mechanism
is intended to introduce new commands by APL libraries. Like system commands,
user-define commands can only be executed in immediate execution mode and not
from user-defined functions or from тНО. It is not intended to extend the
functionality of user-defined commands beyond what is being described in the
following.

A user-defined command ]NEW_COMMAND is created with the debug command
]USERCMD like this:

@verbatim
      ]USERCMD ]NEW_COMMAND APL_FUNCTION [mode]
@end verbatim

APL_FUNCTION is an APL function that will be called when the command is
entered in immediate execution mode. The entire line entered by the user,
starting at ]NEW_COMMAND, is the right argument of APL_FUNCTION. If mode is
missing (or 0) then APL_FUNCTION is called monadically. If mode is 1 then
APL_FUNCTION is called dyadically; the left argument is a vector of strings
that is the left argument broken down into individual argument strings.

The function APL_FUNCTION that implements a command need not exist when the
command is created.

A single user-defined command ]UCMD, or all user-defined commands can
be deleted like this:

@verbatim
      ]USERCMD REMOVE ]UCMD
      ]USERCMD REMOVE-ALL
@end verbatim

@c ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
@node    Section 2.16
@section Structured Variables and Associative Arrays

GNU APL has implemented two features that are closely related because, under
the hood, they share the same implementation: @b{structured variables} and
@b{associative arrays}.

@c ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
@subsection Structured Variables

A structured variable is an APL variable that contains several related but
otherwise independent sub-variables aka. @b{members}. Such structured variables
can be convenient for passing many related arguments to a function, or
for returning multiple results from a function.

The different sub-variables of a structured variable are accessed by the
(top-level) name of the variable followed by a non-empty sequence of member
names, separated by '.'. In the following we will use uppercase names for
structured variables and lowercase names for their members. For example:

@verbatim
      PERSON.address.street
@end verbatim

is a structured variable @b{PERSON}, which has a member @b{address},
and @b{PERSON.address} is a structured (sub-)variable of PERSON which has
a member @b{street}.

For a structured variable and all its sub-variables, the usual rules for
normal variables apply. They can be created, erased, and even passed as
arguments to functions. @b{Nota bene}: Some GNU APL operators are implemented
as macros (i.e. internal defined APL functions). The macros may call APL
primitives that invalidate the fact that a value is structured and, as a
consequence, the operator results may become plain APL values. If this happens,
the structured nature of a plain APL value can be restored with 38 тОХCR.

A structured variable is created by assigning a value to one of its members.
For example:

@verbatim
      PERSON.firstname тЖР 'Jane' тНЭ create variable PERSON with member 'firstname'
      PERSON.lastname  тЖР 'Doe'  тНЭ add a second member 'lastname' to PERSON
@end verbatim

The depth of a newly created member can be more than one. In this case the
intermediate members are created automatically. For example:

@verbatim
      PERSON.address.street тЖР '42 Main Street' тНЭ implicitly creates PERSON.address
@end verbatim

Empty structured variables can be created with @b{38 тОХCR}:

@verbatim
      EMPTY тЖР 38 тОХCR CAPACITY тЖР 32
@end verbatim

Note: A structured variable is automatically expanded when new members are
added to it. From time to time this expansion exceeds the space allocated
for the members of the variable and then the existing members need to be
copied into a new, larger structure. The overhead caused by this reorganization
can be avoided by specifying a sufficiently large capacity when the structure
is created (with @b{38 тОХCR}).

An entire structured variable can be erased with @b{тОХEX} or with
@b{)ERASE} just like other variables. They erase the variable along
with all its members. In addition to erasing an entire structured variable,
individual members at any depth can also be erased with @b{тОХEX} or
@b{)ERASE}:

@verbatim
      )ERASE PERSON.address      тНЭ OK, PERSON.address exists
      )ERASE PERSON.address      тНЭ error: PERSON.address does not exist anymore
NOT ERASED: PERSON.address
@end verbatim

After having been created, the members of a structured variable can be
referenced and overwritten just like normal variables:

@verbatim
      PERSON.address.street тЖР  '42 Main Street'   тНЭ create member address.street
      PERSON.address.street   тНЭ reference member address.street of PERSON
42 Main Street

      PERSON.address.street тЖР  '44 Main Street'   тНЭ overwrite address.street
      PERSON.address.street
44 Main Street
@end verbatim

The members of a structured variable form a tree of (sub-) variables, similar
to the file system on a computer. This tree has:

@itemize
@item one root (which is the structured variable itself),

@item zero or more non-leafs (like sub-directories of the top-level root
  directory), and

@item zero or more leafs. The case of zero non-leafs occurs, for example,
directly after a new empty variable was created with @b{38 тОХCR}.
@end itemize

Due to their tree-like structure, structured variables need to be printed
somewhat differently than normal APL variables. For example:

@verbatim
      PERSON
.firstname: тФМтЖТтФАтФАтФАтФР
            тФВJaneтФВ
            тФФтФАтФАтФАтФАтФШ

.lastname: тФМтЖТтФАтФАтФР
           тФВDoeтФВ
           тФФтФАтФАтФАтФШ

.address: 
.address.street: тФМтЖТтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФР
                 тФВ44 Main StreetтФВ
                 тФФтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФАтФШ
@end verbatim

Only the leafs of a deeply structured variable can have values and, as a
precaution, assigning a value to a non-leaf (including the root) raises
a DOMAIN ERROR:

@verbatim
      B.b.cтЖР'leaf-Abc'        тНЭ OK, since B.b.c will be a leaf
      B.bтЖР42                  тНЭ will fail since B.b is not a leaf
DOMAIN ERROR+
      B.bтЖР42
       ^ ^
      )MORE
member access: cannot override non-leaf member A.b
)ERASE or тОХEX that member first.

      )ERASE B.b
      B.b тЖР 'leaf-Ab'         тНЭ now OK, since B.b will now become a (new) leaf

      )SIC
@end verbatim

On the other hand, assigning a structured variable to the leaf of another
structured variable is valid and concatenates the members:

@verbatim
      )ERASE A
      A.b.c тЖР 'leaf-Abc'      тНЭ variable A with leaf A.b.c
      C.d.e тЖР 'leaf-cde'      тНЭ variable C with leaf C.d.e
      A.b.c тЖР C               тНЭ overwrite leaf A.b.c of A
      A.b.c.d.e
leaf-cde
@end verbatim

The file @b{src/testcases/Structured_variable.tc} contains the examples
above (and more) 

