@subsection Associative Arrays

APL arrays are primarily indexed with numbers (or arrays of numbers), which
is also the most efficient method. Many other languages provide, either in
addition or else alternatively, a method to index arrays by @b{keys}, where
the keys are frequently character strings. Such arrays are commonly referred
to as @b{associative arrays}.

APL has no associative array per se, but the structured variables in GNU APL
can be used for the same purpose. The only limitation is (currently) that the
keys need to be character strings (as opposed to arbitrary APL values).

That is, in GNU APL an associative array

@itemize
@item is a structured variable, and
@item can be indexed with arbitrary (!) strings
@end itemize

As long as the strings that are used as keys follow the same rules as APL
variable names (no leading digit, no '.' etc.), a structured variable can
also be indexed with a string. That can be useful if keys are being computed
or passed as function arguments. However, unlike indexing of APL arrays with
numbers, only one key per (bracket-) index is permitted.

@verbatim
   A.key тЖР 42
   A.key
42
   A['key']
42
   A['key']тЖР24
   A.key
24
   A['key' 'key']   тНЭ not allowed even though 'key' is a valid member
DOMAIN ERROR
      D['key' 'key']

@end verbatim

Strings that do not follow the rules for variable names can be used with
bracket index, but not with the .member syntax:

@verbatim
      ASSOC тЖР 38 тОХCR 8
      KEYтЖР'key.dot'   тНЭ works, but avoid such keys
      ASSOC[KEY]тЖР42
      ASSOC[KEY]
42
      ASSOC[KEY]тЖР43
      ASSOC[KEY]
43
      ASSOC.key.dot   тНЭ won't work: 'key.dot' is a single key, but key.dot is 2 keys
VALUE ERROR+
      ASSOC.key.dot
               ^
      )MORE
member access: structure ASSOC has no member key

      ASSOC.key.dotтЖР44   тНЭ works: 2 (nested) keys
      ASSOC.key.dot
44
      ASSOC['key.dot']   тНЭ works: one key containing '.'
43
@end verbatim

This is because ASSOC.key.dot above is being tokenized by the APL parser into
[ASSOC] [key] [dot], while 'key.dot' is a single key. The example above (with
different values for ASSOC.key.dot and for ASSOC['key.dot'] demonstrates why
such keys are better avoided.

Even though (one) bracket index can only access the top-level members of a
structured variable, repeated bracket index (or dyadic PICK) can be used to
access deeper nesting levels:

@verbatim
      D.b.cтЖР42
      D['b.c']   тНЭ will fail
INDEX ERROR+
      D['b.c']
      ^^
      )MORE
member access: member b.c was not found. The valid members are:
      b

      D['b']['c']   тНЭ will work
42

      тНЭ alternatively: use PICK
      тНЭ
      'b' 'c' тКГ D   тНЭ fails: 'b' 'c' is 'bc'
      "b" "c" тКГ D   тНЭ works
42

@end verbatim

In the above examples each bracket index (or each element of PICK) discards the
current top-level structure and descends into the structured sub-variable of
the chosen member. In this case PICK is more efficient since repeated bracket
index creates copies of the intermediate structured sub-variables.

If a variable is used as a structured variable then the number of its members
is typically small (since every member name occurs explicitly in the APL code
that uses it). If a variable is used as an associative array, then the member
names are typically being computed and the number of members can become rather
large (like the different key values in a database). When such a variable
(i.e. with many members) reaches its capacity, then finding a member (when
the array is indexed), or finding an unused place in the variable (when a new
member is added) becomes slower and slower. The GNU APL implementation has
addressed this by hashing into the variable (based on the member name)
instead of, for example, sequentially allocating the members. This is very
fast under normal circumstances, but becomes as slow as sequential allocation
when the number of members in the variable reaches its current capacity.
For this reason, if a structured variable is used as an associative array,
e.g. as a database, then it is better to not rely on the (automatic)
reorganization of the variable, but to create a large enough variable
(with 38 тОХCR) from the beginning.

If that is not possible (because the (performance-) problem has occurred after
the variable was created, then one can manually increase the capacity like this:

@verbatim
      TMP тЖР 39 тОХCR ASSOC_ARRAY   тНЭ save ASSOC_ARRAY as normal APL array
      тКг тОХEX 'ASSOC_ARRAY'        тНЭ erase it so that it can be assigned
      ASSOC_ARRAY тЖР 38 тОХCR TMP   тНЭ new associative array with тЙе twice the size
@end verbatim

As a rule of thumb, associative arrays will be fast as long their capacity is
more than twice the number of their members. The expression ASSOC_ARRAY[;1]
returns all keys (= members) of ASSOC_ARRAY, therefore the number of members
is тН┤ASSOC_ARRAY[;1] and the capacity is тЖСтН┤ASSOC_ARRAY.


@node    Section 2.17
@section Monadic тКв and тКг, dyadic тКв with Axis

Monadic тКв is the identity function. It returns its (committed or non-committed)
right argument as a non-committed value.

Conversely, monadic тКг (called @b{Hide} in GNU APL) discards its (committed or
non-committed) right argument and returns a committed integer scalar 0. 

For the most part there is no difference between a committed value (= a value
that was assigned to a variable, including тОХ and тНЮ) and a non-committed value.
The point where it does make a difference is when the value is the final result
of a statement (as opposed to an intermediate result inside a statement). In
that situation (and only there) a non-committed value is printed but a
committed value is not.

You can use тКв in a similar fashion as тОХтЖР at the left end of a statement,
to print a value even though it was previously assigned to a variable.

The main motivation for тКг is that, at least in GNU APL, lambdas always return
a value. However, if a lambda is used only for the sake of its side effects,
say to print something, then the value returned by the lambda is often of no
interest and only messes up the APL output. In that situation тКг can be used
to suppress the printing of undesired return values from lambdas.

In earlier GNU APL versions, тКгB and тКвB would both return B; with тКг as committed
value and with тКв as non-committed value. But since the only real-life purpose
of тКг is to suppress the printing of B, the implementation of тКг was changed to
returning a committed integer scalar 0 instead of committed B. That reduced
the run-time of тКгB from O(,B) to O(1). Also, тКвB is marginally faster than тОХтЖРB.

Dyadic тКв with axis is a selection function that generalizes тКг and тКв.

Let @b{ZтЖРA тКг[X] B}. Then:

@itemize
@item if X is a one-element vector and тЖСX is 0 then Z тЙб A,
@item if X is a one-element vector and тЖСX is 1 then Z тЙб B,
@item otherwise X selects items of A or B if the corresponding elements of
X are 0 or 1 respectively. In that case, the shapes of A and B must match
the shape of X, but one-element A or B are scalar extended to the shape of X.
@end itemize

Example:
@verbatim

      AтЖР2 3тН┤'abcdef'
      BтЖР2 3тН┤тН│6
      XтЖР2 3тН┤0 1 0 1 0 1
      A тКв[X] B
a 2 c
4 e 6

   A тКв[X] '*'
a*c
*e*

  '*' тКв[X] B
* 2 *
4 * 6
@end verbatim


@node    Section 2.18
@section Bit-wise Logical Functions тКдтИз, тКдтИи, тКдтН▓, тКдтН▒, тКдтЙа, and тКд=

The APL functions And (тИз), Or (тИи), Nand (тН▓), and Nor (тН▒) operate primarily on
Boolean integers. Primarily means that the LCM variant for тИз and the GCD
variant for тИи are not considered in this context. (The LCM and GCD variants
are defined in the ISO standard and supported in GNU APL but not in IBM APL2).

However, probably more often than not one needs to compute Boolean functions
between the bits of arbitrary (non-Boolean) integers and not between entire
Boolean integers 0 or 1. Although that is possible to do in standard APL,
the procedure is fairly awkward and, more importantly, inefficient:

@itemize
@item
convert every integer argument X to a 64-item Boolean vector XтЖР(64тН┤2)тКдX,
@item
call the Boolean function тИз, тИи, тН▓, тН▒, =, or тЙа with the converted arguments,
and
@item
convert the Boolean result vector R back to the integer result ZтЖР2тКеR
@end itemize

Note: for Boolean arguments the APL functions тЙа and = can be used to compute
the more customary Boolean functions XOR and XNOR respectively. In this context
= and тЙа are treated as Boolean functions even though they accept non-Boolean
arguments,

For example, using  5 тОХCR (4тН┤256)тКдX to display X in hex:

@verbatim
      5 тОХCR (4тН┤256)тКд   AтЖР$ABBADEAD
ABBADEAD
      5 тОХCR (4тН┤256)тКд   BтЖР$00FF00FF
00FF00FF

      5 тОХCR (4тН┤256)тКд   2тКе ((64тН┤2)тКдA) тИз (64тН┤2)тКдB
00BA00AD

@end verbatim

With the bit-wise @b{And} (тКдтИз) the same can be achieved in a simpler fashion
and far more efficiently:

@verbatim
      тНЭ Traditional AND
      5 тОХCR (4тН┤256)тКд   AтЖР$ABBADEAD
ABBADEAD
      5 тОХCR (4тН┤256)тКд   BтЖР$00FF00FF
00FF00FF

      тНЭ bit-wise AND
      5 тОХCR (4тН┤256)тКд   A тКдтИз B
00BA00AD
@end verbatim

@subsection Dyadic тКдтИз, тКдтИи, тКдтН▓, тКдтН▒, тКд=, and тКдтЙа

The dyadic forms of @b{тКдтИз}, @b{тКдтИи}, @b{тКдтН▓}, and @b{тКдтН▒} are simply the bit-wise
variants of their Boolean counterparts:

@verbatim
      A тКдтИз B    тЖРтЖТ    2тКе ((64тН┤2)тКдA) тИз (64тН┤2)тКдB      тНЭ aka. AND
      A тКдтИи B    тЖРтЖТ    2тКе ((64тН┤2)тКдA) тИи (64тН┤2)тКдB      тНЭ aka. OR
      A тКдтН▓ B    тЖРтЖТ    2тКе ((64тН┤2)тКдA) тН▓ (64тН┤2)тКдB      тНЭ aka. NAND
      A тКдтН▒ B    тЖРтЖТ    2тКе ((64тН┤2)тКдA) тН▒ (64тН┤2)тКдB      тНЭ aka. NOR
      A тКдтЙа B    тЖРтЖТ    2тКе ((64тН┤2)тКдA) тЙа (64тН┤2)тКдB      тНЭ aka. XOR
      A тКд= B    тЖРтЖТ    2тКе ((64тН┤2)тКдA) = (64тН┤2)тКдB      тНЭ aka. NXOR or XNOR
@end verbatim

@subsection Monadic тКдтИи and тКдтН▒

@b{тКд=}, @b{тКдтЙа}, and @b{тКдтН▓} do not have a monadic form, but @b{тКдтИз}, @b{тКдтИи},
and @b{тКдтН▒} do.
Formally monadic @b{тКдтИи} and @b{тКдтН▒} are dyadic @b{тКдтИи} and @b{тКдтН▒} with
a left argument of 0:

@verbatim
      тКдтИи B    тЖРтЖТ    0 тКдтИи B      тНЭ real B to nearby integer
      тКдтН▒ B    тЖРтЖТ    0 тКдтН▒ B      тНЭ bit-wise Not
@end verbatim

Even though Or-ing a Boolean vector with 0 itself has no effect, the
monadic тКдтИи and тКдтН▒ are still useful due to their side effects: conversion
from near-integer float values to integers (monadic @b{тКдтИи} and inversion
of the bits (monadic @b{тКдтН▒}, The latter is needed since тИ╝ has a monadic
form and, as a consequence, тКдтИ╝ was not an option for a bit-wise @b{Not}
function.

Monadic @b{тКдтН▒ B} is the bit-wise @b{Not} function of its argument:

      тКдтН▒ B    тЖРтЖТ    2тКе ~(64тН┤2)тКдB

Monadic @b{тКдтИи B} converts near-integer values B into true integers:

@verbatim
      26 тОХCR    1            тНЭ integer
16
      26 тОХCR    1.1          тНЭ real
32
      26 тОХCR    1├╖1          тНЭ integer
16
      26 тОХCR    1.1├╖1.1      тНЭ real
32
      26 тОХCR    тКдтИи 1.1├╖1.1   тНЭ integer
16
@end verbatim

That also works for complex numbers with a near-zero imaginary part:

@verbatim
      26 тОХCR    1.1J0├╖1.1      тНЭ real
32
      26 тОХCR    тКдтИи 1.1J0├╖1.1      тНЭ integer
16
@end verbatim

As a matter of fact, @b{тКдтИи} works for all near-Gaussian complex numbers,
but the effect is not visible with 26 тОХCR since Gaussian and non-Gaussian
complex numbers have the same cell type in GNU APL.

@subsection Monadic тКдтИз

The ISO standard defines two different concepts to decide if a real number R
is close to an integer I,
@itemize
@item
the real number R is said to be @b{near} to integer I if the absolute
value of I-R is smaller than some small constant called the @b{integer
tolerance} in ISO and @b{system tolerance} in IBM APL2. The @b{integer
tolerance} is typically platform dependent (1E┬п10 in GNU APL).

@item
the real number R is said to be @b{equal to integer I within тОХCT} if the
absolute value of (I-R)/I is smaller than тОХCT.
@end itemize

The first concept is an absolute distance from a real R to a nearby integer I
while the second concept is a relative distance (larger numbers are allowed to
be farther away from a nearby integer than smaller numbers). The two concepts
differ in the same way that absolute and relative errors do.

Now, all bit-wise functions described so far use the first concept, i,e,
if their arguments are real or complex, then the smallest distance to
a (nearby) integer must not exceed the @b{integer tolerance}. In some contexts
that could be difficult to achieve and for that reason GNU APL provides
monadic тКдтИз which works like тКдтИи except that the permitted distance from a
nearby integer is now controlled by тОХCT rather than by the integer tolerance.

All bit-wise logical functions throw a DOMAIN ERROR if an argument is not close
enough to an integer. The @b{integer tolerance} is typically smaller than тОХCT
and in that case тКдтИз is a little more tolerant than тКдтИи regarding the distance
to nearby integers. In addition тКдтИз gives the user (via тОХCT) more control over
the permitted tolerance for real numbers in the neighborhood of integers.

@subsection Character Arguments for Monadic тКдтН▒ and Dyadic тКдтИз, тКдтИи, ==, and тЙатЙа

Some of the bit-wise operations are allowed to have characters as their right
argument. If the right argument is a character then the result is a character
as well. This can be useful for masking purposes such as extracting the lower
7 bits of 8-bit bytes containing ASCII characters.

The characters involved are treated as 32 bit quantities:

@verbatim
      5тОХCR 'A'
41
      5тОХCR тКдтН▒'A'            тНЭ Note that 5тОХCR aka. тОХCR.to_HEX ANDs with $FF
BE

      256 256 256 256тКд тОХUCS тКдтН▒ 'A'      тНЭ тКдтН▒ 'A' is FFFFFFBE
255 255 255 190
      256 256 256 256тКд$FFFFFFBE
255 255 255 190
@end verbatim


@node    Section 2.19
@section Generalized тН│

@subsection Generalized monadic тН│

The standard function @b{Interval} (ZтЖРтН│B) requires its argument B to be a
positive integer scalar or a length 1 integer vector. The result ZтЖРтН│B then
contains all possible consecutive integer values having shape B.

Generalized monadic тН│ extends this concept to integer vectors B with more
than 1 element. The result ZтЖРтН│B again contains all possible indices of a
value which has shape B, but the rank of B can now be more than 1. The items
of Z are nested integer vectors consecutive along each axis of B as opposed
to integer scalars in the standard case.

@subsection Generalized dyadic тН│

The standard function @b{Index Of} (ZтЖРAтН│B) requires its left argument A to be
a scalar or a vector of rank 1. The items of the result Z are the (first)
positions (= indices) of the matching items of B in A (for the items found
in A) or else тОХIO+тН┤A (which is an invalid index of A) for the items of B that
are not found in A.

Generalized dyadic тН│ extends this concept to find the (first) indices of the
corresponding items of B in A (in ravel order) where the rank of A is > 1.
Each item of the result Z is then either a nested integer vector (if the item
was found) or @b{- different from the standard case (!) -} the empty vector тНм
if the item was not found).


@node    Section 2.20
@section тМ╣[X] - QR Factorization

ZтЖРтМ╣[X] B computes a QR factorization of the real or complex matrix B. The
axis argument X is used to clear near-0 matrix items to exactly 0.0 during
the computation. Set XтЖРтОХCT if unsure.

The result Z is a triple (QT R Ri)тЖРZ with the following properties.
Let тН┤B=(M, N).

* QT is an orthogonal M├ЧM matrix, i.e QT@sup{-1} = QT@sup{T}, and QT +.├Ч тНЙQT
 is the M├ЧM identity matrix I@sub{M} (with I@sub{M}тЖРтИШ.=тНитН│M).

* R is an upper triangular M├ЧN matrix, i.e. R[m;n] = 0 for n < m, and

* Ri is the inverse of R, i.e. Ri +.├Ч R is the identity matrix I@sub{N}.

* (тНЙQT) +.├Ч R = B.

Note that, unlike in standard QR factorizations, the matrix QT returned by
тМ╣[X] is already inverted (i.e. transposed since QT is orthogonal). The
reason is that the algorithm used can transpose Q with no extra cost and
usually the first step after a QR factorization is to transpose the
returned Q matrix. This first transpose step is therefore not needed.

Example 1 (real B)
@verbatim

      тКвBтЖР3 3тН┤ 1 1 3 2 4 2 4 8 7
1 1 3
2 4 2
4 8 7

      (QT R Ri)тЖРтМ╣[тОХCT]B
      QтЖРтНЙQT           тНЭ recover the non-transposed Q

      4тОХCR0 4тНХQ
