@subsection The Impact of тОХCT for тМ╣

Due to the lack of a better place we describe here how @b{тОХCT} is used
in the various @b{тМ╣} functions.

@subsubsection AтМ╣B and тМ╣B

The first step in the computation of @b{AтМ╣B} or @b{тМ╣B} is the estimation
of the number of linearly independent columns of @b{B}. If that number is
smaller than the total number of columns (IOW some columns of @b{B} are
linearly dependent) then a @b{DOMAIN ERROR} is raised before the computation
of @b{тМ╣B} starts. Although @b{B} may be over-determined (so it may have more
rows than columns and in that case the rows of @b{B} cannot be linearly
independent) it may @i{not} have linearly dependent columns.

Now, for every real or complex number @b{тН║} does @b{тОХCT} define a range
of nearby numbers that are considered equal to @b{тН║} even though they are,
computationally speaking, different?

In the same fashion, let @b{B} be a matrix with linearly dependent columns.
For every such @b{B} does @b{тОХCT} define a range of nearby matrices that
are also considered linearly dependent even though they are, strictly
speaking, linearly independent? As a matter of fact, the probability
that the columns of @b{B} are strictly linearly independent decreases
as the size of the matrix grows. If a matrix has linearly dependent
columns, then every new row added to the matrix can make it linearly
independent, but not the other way around.

The consequence for the user of GNU APL is the following. If GNU APL raises
a @b{DOMAIN ERROR} caused by the supposedly linearly dependent columns of some
matrix @b{B} then there are two possibilities:

@enumerate
@item the columns of @b{B} are indeed linearly dependent, e.g. @b{тМ╣BтЖР2 2тН┤3 4}.
      In this case there is no way to compute @b{тМ╣B}.
@item the columns of @b{B} are only close (as controlled by @b{тОХCT}) to
      some other strictly linearly dependent matrix. In this case (which
      is far more likely than the other), one may decrease @b{тОХCT}
      until the matrix becomes linearly independent. For example, @b{тМ╣B}
      may raise a DOMAIN ERROR with the default @b{тОХCTтЖР1E┬п13} but not
      with @b{тОХCTтЖР1E┬п15}.
      However, one should use this technique with great care because
      matrices that are nearly linearly dependent tend to produce
      significant rounding errors in the result.
@end enumerate

@subsubsection тМ╣[X] B

The integer scalar @b{X} chooses one of currently two different algorithms
that compute a QR factorization of a matrix @b{B}:

@itemize
@item @b{тМ╣[1]B} uses the algorithm published by Garry Helzer in APL Quote
      Quad in 1990.
@item @b{тМ╣[2]B} uses a LApack algorithm (xGELSY). This algorithm uses
      @b{тОХCT} in the same way as described above for @b{тМ╣B} and @b{AтМ╣B}.
@item for backward compatibility with older versions of GNU APL, a real 
      scalar @b{X} in @b{тМ╣[X]B} uses @b{тМ╣[1]B} if @b{X < 0.1} and
      @b{тМ╣[2]B} otherwise. The scalar @b{X} is used instead of @b{тОХCT}.
      Do not use this case in new code.
@end itemize

The Helzer algorithm recursively factors a N├ЧN matrix, a (N-1)├Ч(N-1) matrix,
a (N-2)├Ч(N-2) matrix, and so forth. After every step of that recursion,
all matrix items close to 0.0 are set to exactly 0.0.

GNU APL uses @b{тОХCT} in the same way as the Helzer alogrithm, i.e. to decide
if a matrix item close to 0.0 shall be set to 0.0 or not (APL functions
@b{A TOL X} and @b{A CPR B}, where Helzer leaves it open how to
implement @b{A TOL X} and @b{A CPR B}). GNU APL uses the example
implementation given in the Helzer paper. The @b{TOL} and @b{CPR}
functions seem to be related to what is elsewhere known as the
@i{condition number} of the matrix that is being factorized. In the LApack
case, the parameter @b{RCOND} of FORTRAN function @b{xcDGELSY} is set
to @b{тОХCT}.


@node    Section 2.21
@section Dyadic тОХCR

The тОХCR function has an optional left argument that selects one of several
formatting styles and conversion functions in addition to the well-known
monadic form.

Calling тОХCR monadically without an axis and with an empty right argument
shows a list of all functions provided by тОХCR:

@verbatim
      тОХCR ''
@end verbatim

Say a @b{byte vector} is an integer vector with numbers having a (signed or
unsigned) 8-bit value (i.e. a value from -128 to 255 inclusive). Such byte
vectors are frequently used arguments and results of тОХFIO functions.

Let ZтЖРA тОХCR B.

Then the left argument A of тОХCR selects one of several sub-functions of тОХCR:

A=0-4 or 7-9, or 29: various formatting styles (boxed, APL input/output, etc.).
Just try them out.

A=5 or 6: convert byte vector B to a string of uppercase or lowercase
hex digits respectively. Every byte in B becomes 2 characters in Z.

A=10: convert variable named in B to an APL expression producing it.

A=11: convert value B to byte vector Z in CDR ("Common Data Representation",
an IBM standard) format (similar to 3 тОХTF).

A=12: convert byte vector B in CDR format to value Z.

A=13: convert hex string B to byte vector Z.

If a conversion has an inverse conversion (like 12 being the inverse of 11)
then the inverse conversion can be expressed as the negative of the conversion
number. For example, 12 тОХCR B is the same as ┬п11 тОХCR B.

A=14: conversion 11 followed by conversion 13 (Value to hex string in
CDR format)

A=15: conversion 13 followed by conversion 12 (hex string in CDR format
to Value)

A=16: encode byte vector B into Z (base64 encoding, RFC 4648)

A=17: decode base64 vector B into byte vector Z (base64 encoding, RFC 4648)

A=18: convert text vector B into byte vector Z (UTF8 encoding, RFC 3629) 

A=19: convert byte vector B into text vector Z (UTF8 encoding, RFC 3629)

A=20-25: like 3,4,7-9 but using a formatting similar to NARS APL тОХFMT
(showing the axis lengths as numbers instead of тЖТ and тЖУ)

A=26: Z is the cell types of the ravel elements of B (2: character,
16: integer, 32: real number, 64: complex number.

A=27: Z[I] is the primary data representation (for example the real part 
of a complex number, or the numerator of a rational number) of B[I].

A=28: Z[I] is the additional data representation (for example the imaginary
part of a complex number, or the denominator of a rational number) of B[I].

A=30: Z is B with all top-level elements conformed to a common rank and
shape (as required by the тНд operator). This conversion is primarily used 
internally by the GNU APL interpreter.

A=31 or A=32: These conversions are used internally by тОХINP.

A=33: convert tagged byte vector to a TLV (Tag/Length/Value) buffer. The TLV
buffer can be sent over a byte stream (socket) and easily decoded at the other
end. Say B = B[1], B[2], ..., B[n] such that B1 is an Integer (the tag) and
B[j] is a character in the range 0-255 for j > 1. Let ZтЖР33 тОХCR B with
Z = Z[1], Z[2], ... Z[m]. Then Z[1 2 3 4] is the 4 byte tag, Z[5 6 7 8]
is the 4 byte data length (n-1) == (m - 8) and 1тЖУB == 8 тЖУ Z. In other words,
the first 4 bytes of Z are the tag in big endian byte order, the next 4 bytes
are the length of B except the tag, and the rest of Z is B except the tag.

Example:
@verbatim
      TagтЖР55   тНЭ hex 37
      5 тОХCR 33 тОХCR Tag,'Value'
000000370000000556616C7565
@end verbatim

A=34: this is the inverse of 33 тОХCR. The intended use for 33 тОХCR and 34 тОХCR
is the transmission of a tagged byte vector over e.g a TCP socket:

  Sender                                          Receiver
  ------                                          --------
  T,Data тЖТтЖТтЖТ 33 тОХCR T,Data   тЖТтЖТтЖТTCP connectionтЖТтЖТтЖТ   34 тОХCR T,Data тЖТтЖТтЖТ T,Data

Example:
@verbatim
      34 тОХCR ┬п5 тОХCR '000000370000000556616C7565'
55 Value
@end verbatim

The TLVs constructed by 33 тОХCR can be sent back-to-back over a TCP connection
or similar in such a way that the receiver knows exactly after which byte
a TLV ends, which is perfect for connections over which data is sent
sporadically. 33 тОХCR and 34 тОХCR are particularly useful for encoding and
decoding TLV byte buffers exchanged between GNU APL and processes that were
forked by GNU APL with тОХFIO[57] (aka. fork() and execve()).

Most dyadic тОХCR variants whose argument B is expected to be a byte vector throw:

@enumerate
@item RANK ERROR if 1тЙатН┤тН┤B
@item DOMAIN ERROR if one of the B[j] is not a proper byte value
@end enumerate

A proper byte value is either an integer in the range -128...255 inclusive,
or a (Unicode) character with a code point between U+FF80 and U+FFFF
(inclusive, corresponding to a negative signed char in C/C++) or between
U+0000...U+00FF (inclusive, corresponding to an unsigned char or to a signed
positive char in C/C++). Real, Complex, or rational numbers are never proper
byte values even if their value is close to an integer. Nor are nested APL
values or values being assigned.


@node    Section 2.22
@section  Dyadic тОХFX (Native Functions)

A Native Function is a function that can be called in APL like a normal user
defined APL function, but is implemented in C++.

A native function is created with A тОХFX B. A is a string that is the
path of a shared library and B is the name of the function in APL.

The GNU APL package contains a shared library file_io.so that contains the
implementation of a native function for reading and writing files (fopen(),
fclose(), ...), For example:

@verbatim
      тНЭ fix native function in lib_file_io.so as FILE_IO
      тНЭ
      'lib_file_io.so' тОХFX 'FILE_IO'
FILE_IO

      тНЭ show overview of sub-functions in FILE_IO
      тНЭ
      FILE_IO ''
   Functions provided by this library.
   Assumes 'lib_file_io.so'  тОХFX  'FUN'

   Legend: e - error code
           i - integer
           h - file handle (integer)
           s - string
           A1, A2, ...  nested vector with elements A1, A2, ...

           FUN     ''    print this text on stderr
        '' FUN     ''    print this text on stdout
           FUN[ 0] ''    print this text on stderr
        '' FUN[ 0] ''    print this text on stdout

   Zi тЖР    FUN[ 1] ''    errno (of last call)
   Zs тЖР    FUN[ 2] Be    strerror(Be)
   Zh тЖР As FUN[ 3] Bs    fopen(Bs, As) filename Bs mode As
   Zh тЖР    FUN[ 3] Bs    fopen(Bs, "r") filename Bs
      ...
@end verbatim

Recent versions of GNU APL have replaced the native FILE_IO function above by
the system function тОХFIO. тОХFIO need not be тОХFX'ed and is otherwise backward
compatible to the native function. New function numbers are, however, only
added to тОХFIO and not to the old native function FILE_IO. The parameters of
the functions are described in the man pages for, e.g. strerror, fopen, ...
and are fairly obvious.

Many functions in FILE_IO have byte vectors as arguments or return byte 
vectors. A byte vector is an integer vector whose numbers fit into a byte
(so they are integers between -128 and 255). Often тОХUCS and the functions in
dyadic тОХCR are used to convert such byte vectors to/from, for example,
Unicode strings.

The GNU APL package also contains other shared libraries as templates
for your own native functions. Copy one of the files
src/native/template_F0.cc (for niladic native functions),
src/native/template_F12.cc (for nomadic native functions),
src/native/template_OP1.cc (for monadic native operators),
or src/native/template_OP2/cc (for dyadic native operators) to your own
.cc file and adjust src/native/Makefile.am accordingly.

Note: The )IN and )OUT commands of GNU APL support native functions, but
to do so they have to use dyadic тОХFX. This renders the workspace
interchange file (.atf files) written by )OUT incompatible with all other
APL interpreters if the workspace contains native functions. The )OUT 
command prints a warning when it is used with a workspace that contains
native functions.

Note: As of GNU APL 1.6, the native function FILE_IO has been turned into the
system function тОХFIO. The syntax of тОХFIO is the same as for FILE_IO. The
)CLEAR workspace command will close all open files. 


@node    Section 2.23
@section тОХARG - Interpreter command line arguments

тОХARG contains the command line arguments with which GNU APL was invoked.
@xref{Section 2.1}.


@node    Section 2.24
@section тОХDLX - Knuth's Dancing Links Algorithm

тОХDLX is an implementation of Donald Knuth's Dancing Links Algorithm (called
DLX by Knuth himself, but is sometimes also referred to as Knuth's Algorithm X).
тОХDLX is a generic backtracking machine that can be used to dramatically
simplify problems like the 8 queens problem on a chess board or sudokus.

The monadic form of тОХDLX, i.e. тОХDLX B, is a shortcut for 0 тОХDLX B. It
computes the first solution for the constraint matrix B.

The dyadic form of тОХDLX, i.e. A тОХDLX B, has an integer scalar A as left
argument which determines the details of the computation as follows:

A > 0: The algorithm tries to find all solutions, but stops when A solutions
have been found. This is handy while debugging code using тОХDLX. The
result is a nested vector with one vector item per solution.

A = 0: The algorithm stops when the first solution was found. In this case
the solution is a simple (non-nested) numeric vector.

A = ┬п1: like A > 0 but finding all solutions

A = ┬п2: like A = 0 but instead of returning the first solution, the number of
solutions (i.e. 0 or 1), the number of backtracks, and the number of
link dances is returned as a 3-element numeric vector.

A = ┬п3: like A = ┬п1 but instead of returning all solutions, the number of
solutions, the number of backtracks, and the number of link dances is
returned as a 3-element numeric vector.

A = ┬п4: A number of single steps in Knuth's Algorithm are performed. Let e.g.
AтЖР┬п4 r1 r2 r3. Then ZтЖРA тОХDLX B is the matrix B after 3 steps r1, r2, and r3
have been performed. r1, r2, and r3 are valid (as per тОХIO) row numbers of B,
and a step with a given row changes B as follows:
@itemize
@item
the given row is set to 0 (this row becomes part of the final result),
@item
all other rows that have a 1 or a 2 in the same column as B are set to 0
(these 1s or 2s in the other rows conflict with the 1 or 2 in the given row
and are therefore removed from B), and
@item
all columns that have no 1s or 2s left are removed from B (these columns have
a 1 or 2 in B and the constraint is therefore satisfied).
@end itemize
The purpose of ┬п4 тОХDLX is:
@itemize
@item
To demonstrate how Knuth's algorithm works, and/or
@item
To preset some initial values in B. For example, one can first initialize
the constraints for an empty Sudoku (which is the same matrix for all Sudokus)
and then enter the initial digits of a particular Sudoku using 4 тОХDLX. If there are, say, 20 initial digits in the Sudoku then A has 21 elements (┬п4 plus the
20 rows representing the 20 initial digits. The result of ┬п4 тОХDLX B has the
same number of rows as B (with some rows now cleared), but fewer columns than B.
@end itemize

The right argument B of тОХDLX B or A тОХDLX B is a constraints matrix whose
columns consist of either 0s and 1s (called a primary column) or 0s and 2s
(called secondary columns). The 0s, 1s and 2s can be the integers 0, 1, or 2,
characters '0', '1', or '2' respectively, or ' ' meaning '0'. The character
representation is useful when B becomes large and shall be printed because
the spaces in the numerical variant will not be printed. In the following,
B is assumed to be numeric.

Let ZтЖРA тОХDLX B, and let R be a solution in Z, that is, Z itself (A = 0) or
R is Z[k] for some k if A тЙа 0. And let SтЖР+тМ┐B[R].

Then S = s1 s2 s3, ... sN where N is the number of columns in B and sj=1
if j is a primary column of B and sjтИИ0 1 if j is a secondary column of B.

In other words, тОХDLX B computes a subset of the rows of B in such a way that
for every column j of B exactly one (for primary column j) or at most one
(for a secondary column) of the rows in a solution has its j'th element set
to 1 and all other words set their j'th element set to 0.

In yet other words, for every solution returned by тОХDLX B, a 1 in one row
prevents all other rows that also have a 1 in that column, and all rows
together have exactly one 1 in every primary column and at most one 1 in
every secondary column. In the absence of secondary columns, the problem
solved by тОХDLX is also known as the "exact cover problem"

If all that sounds weird and useless, consider the following APL program
for finding all solutions of the 8 Queens problem on a chess board (which
probably every programmer has programmed at some point in time):

@verbatim
      RCтЖР8тЖС'1' тЧК DтЖР15тЖС┬п8тЖС'2'   тНЭ helpers for constructing Q8
      тНЭ     rows   cols   diag1    diag2
      Q8тЖРтКГ{(RтМ╜RC),(CтМ╜RC),((C-R)тМ╜D),((┬п7-R+C)тМ╜D)тКг(R C)тЖР-8 8тКдтН╡-тОХIO} ┬и тН│64
      ZтЖР┬п1 тОХDLX Q8
      {тОХUCS (65+тМКтН╡├╖8)(49+8тИгтН╡тЖРтН╡-тОХIO)} ┬и тКГZ[1 2 3 92] тНЭ solutions 1, 2, 3, and 92
 A1 B5 C8 D6 G2 E3 F7 H4 
 A1 B6 C8 D3 E7 F4 G2 H5 
 A1 B7 C4 E8 D6 G5 F2 H3 
 A8 B4 C1 D3 G7 E6 F2 H5 

      8 8тН┤("+" "Q")[тОХIO+(тН│64)тИИтКГZ[1]]   тНЭ visualize solution Z[1]
Q + + + + + + + 
 + + + + Q + + + 
 + + + + + + + Q 
 + + + + + Q + + 
 + + Q + + + + + 
 + + + + + + Q + 
 + Q + + + + + + 
 + + + Q + + + + 

@end verbatim

Obviously Z contains solutions for the 8 Queens problem; the total number of
solutions is well known to be 92 and we showed only the first three and the
last solution above.

The constraint matrix Q8 is the key to success. The matrix has 64 rows - one
row for every field of the chess board. And it has 8 + 8 + 15 + 15 columns.
The first 8 columns of Q8 are constraints that prevent more than one Queen
from being placed in the same row of the chess board (the argument тН╡ is the
field number counting from left to right and from bottom to top).
The next 8 columns of Q8 are constraints that prevent more than one Queen
from being placed in the same column of the chess board.

If we would call тОХDLX with only these constraints, i.e. тОХDLX T8тЖР64 16тЖСQ8,
then we would get the solutions of the 8 tower problem. However, we continue
and add 15 more constraints for each of the two diagonals. The resulting
