Please note that the 'g' flag increments the depth of the result of the output
formats 'string' and 'position/length', but not of the result of output formats
'partition' and 'compress'.

The output formats тКВ and / are related like this:

@verbatim
      A тМ╖RE['/'] B   тЖРтЖТ   0 тЙа A  A тМ╖RE['тКВ'] B
@end verbatim


@subsubsection the тОХRE error flag E

The default behavior of тОХRE is to return an empty result if no match of
the regular expression A is found in B. It is sometimes more convenient to
raise an error if no match is found. This can be achieved with the E flag:

@verbatim
       4 тОХCR 'g..' тОХRE[''] '__foo___fun____fox'
тФПтКЦтФУ
тФГ0тФГ
тФЧтФБтФЫ
       'g..' тОХRE['E'] '__foo___fun____fox'
DOMAIN ERROR+
      'g..' тОХRE['E']'__foo___fun____fox'
      ^            ^
      )MORE
No match
@end verbatim

The 'E' flag has no effect if the 'g' flag is also given because in that case
it is natural to check the length of the result:

@verbatim
      4 тОХCR 'g..' тОХRE['Eg'] '__foo___fun____fox'
тФПтКЦтФУ
тФГ0тФГ
тФЧтФБтФЫ

@end verbatim

@subsection Complex Matches

The regular expressions considered so far were simple, which means that they
did not have (regular) sub-expressions. In other words, the regular expression
A did not contain non-literal (unquoted) parentheses. However, the libpcre2
allows sub-expressions and тОХRE follows suit to a certain extent. If A contains
sub-expressions, the result of A тОХRE B becomes deeper and the structure of the
result is determined by the structure of the parentheses in A.

The result of a general regular expression A is recursively constructed by тОХRE
as follows:

1. If A contains no sub-expressions then the result is constructed as described
   in the previous sections.

2. If A contains sub-expressions, say A1, ... An, then the result is a (nested)
   vector with N+1 elements where the first element is the entire match (which
   contains the sub-matches) and the following elements are the next-level
   sub-matches.

Since the sub-matches are contained in their parent matches, it makes no sense
to handle sub-matches in the partition and compress output formats. For the
string and pos+len formats, the following examples may give some insight into
how the results look.

The regular expression A тЖР 'f(.)(.)' used in the example below is a top-level
regular expression which contains two 1-character sub-expressions (.).
The result is therefore the top-level match plus two 1-character sub-matches:

@verbatim
      4 тОХCR 'f(.)(.)' тОХRE[''] '__foo___fun____fox'
тФПтЖТтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФУ
тФГтФПтЖТтФБтФБтФУ тФПтЖТтФУ тФПтЖТтФУтФГ
тФГтФГfooтФГ тФГoтФГ тФГoтФГтФГ
тФГтФЧтФБтФБтФБтФЫ тФЧтФБтФЫ тФЧтФБтФЫтФГ
тФЧтИКтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФЫ
@end verbatim

Matching all instead of only the first then gives:

@verbatim
      4 тОХCR 'f(.)(.)' тОХRE['g'] '__foo___fun____fox'
тФПтЖТтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФУ
тФГтФПтЖТтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФУ тФПтЖТтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФУ тФПтЖТтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФБтФУтФГ
тФГтФГтФПтЖТтФБтФБтФУ тФПтЖТтФУ тФПтЖТтФУтФГ тФГтФПтЖТтФБтФБтФУ тФПтЖТтФУ тФПтЖТтФУтФГ тФГтФПтЖТтФБтФБтФУ тФПтЖТтФУ тФПтЖТтФУтФГтФГ
