@node    Section 2.40
@section тОХXML  - XML Parsing

@subsection Purpose

GNU APL provides тОХXML as a means of performing @b{elementary}
manipulations of APL character strings that are formatted according
to the XML standard. The anticipated procedure for such modifications
is something like:

@verbatim
      XML_string тЖР "<A><B><C>Hello</C></B></A>"   тНЭ input data (usually from an .xml file)
      APL тЖР тОХXML XML_string       тНЭ convert XML_string to associative array APL
      ABC тЖР APL.a.b.c             тНЭ retrieve node a.b.c in APL
      APL.a.b.c тЖР ABC, " World"   тНЭ modify node a.b.c in APL
      Z тЖР тОХXML APL                тНЭ convert associative array APL to XML string Z

      ABC   тНЭ the original value of XML.a.b.c
Hello
      Z     тНЭ the modified XML string
<A><B><C>Hello World</C></B></A>"
@end verbatim

The scope (functionality) of тОХXML is then:

@itemize
@item Conversion of (valid) XML strings to associative APL arrays that can be
  more easily processed in APL than the XML strings,
@item Conversion of associative APL arrays back to valid XML strings,
@item Simple (at APL level) access to the data contained in XML strings, and
@item Transparent access to those (mostly XML specific) portions of the XML
  string that are not (yet) handled by тОХXML; this means that the user of тОХXML
  shall be able to handle advanced XML aspects (like document type
  declarations (DTDs), document validation, etc.) in APL without much overhead.
@end itemize

@subsection Some XML Terminology

An XML document is a character string with a standardized format.
The characters must be valid XML characters as defined in the XML
standard (almost all Unicode characters except most of the ASCII control
characters). GNU APL raises a DOMAIN ERROR when an XML document contains
invalid XML characters.

The XML document is a sequence of adjacent sub-strings, where each sub-string
is:

@itemize
@item either markup (-string),
@item or non-markup (-string).
@end itemize

A markup (sub-)string:

@itemize
@item starts with character '<', and
@item ends with character '>', and
@item all other characters in the markup string differ from '<' and '>'.
@end itemize

A non-markup (sub-)string:

@itemize
@item starts either at the beginning of the XML document or else directly
      after a markup string,
@item end at the end of the document or else directly before a markup
      string, and therefore
@item cannot be adjacent to another non-markup string.
@end itemize

Non-markup is sometimes referred to as "unstructured text". The producer of
an XML document has a principal choice about where to locate the information
that the document contains: in the unstructured text or in the attribute
values inside the tags. For that reason the XML standard is somewhat picky
about keeping the unstructured text as well as attribute values intact
and requires that whitespace in non-markup (the only allowed whitespace
characters in XML being TAB, CR, LF, and SPACE) is preserved in non-markup
strings.

As a consequence, many non-markup strings begin with LF because the
preceeding markup was on the previous line and therefore the LF after the
preceeding markup is whitespace of the non-markup and therefore needs to be
preserved.

Every markup belongs to one of 4 categories:

@itemize
@item Processing instructions: "<? ... ?>",
@item Comments: "<!--- ... --->",
@item Declarations "<! ... !>", and
@item Tags, which are either:
  @itemize
  @item Empty tags (leaf tags): "<tagname attributes... />
  @item Start tags: "<tagname attributes... >, or
  @item End tags: "</tagname>
  @end itemize
@end itemize

The XML tags recursively define a tree structure where:

@itemize
@item the nodes of the trees are either Empty Tags or else a start tag,
   followed by a (possibly empty) sequence of non-markup, comments, and
   sub-nodes (of the tree), followed by an end tag (with the same name
   as the start tag),
@item the leafs of the trees are either Empty Tags or else a start tag,
   followed by a (possibly empty) sequence of non-markup and comments,
   followed by an end tag (with the same name as the start tag). The difference
   between a leaf node and a non-leaf is therefore the absence of sub-nodes
   between a start and an end tag.
@item optionally non-markup and comments before, after, and between the nodes.
@end itemize

Processing instructions and declarations are typically located at the
beginning of the XML document and at the same level as the root of the tree.
defined by the document. Document type declarations are preserved (so that
they can be processed in APL), but are currently ignored by тОХXML. As a
consequence, entity declarations have no effect and only the predefined XML
entities (i.e. &, <, >, ', and ") are recognized (and translated) by тОХXML.

@subsection How тОХXML maps XML documents to APL Values

The principal mapping between XML strings and APL values is:

@itemize
@item @b{XML document} тЖРтЖТ structured (top-level) APL value or variable
  (= an associative array)
@item @b{XML node} тЖРтЖТ structured APL (sub-) value (= an associative (sub-)
  array of either the top-level value or of another XML node)
@item @b{XML name} тЖРтЖТ name of a member in a structured APL value
@item @b{Other} тЖРтЖТ member value
@end itemize

Every valid name in XML is also a valid name for an APL variable or structure
member. Unfortunately, mapping XML names directly to APL member names cannot
work because:

@itemize
@item In any associative array the names of the members are necessarily
 distinct. Assigning a value to an already existing member of a structured
 value overwrites the current value of that member instead of creating a
 second member with that value. On the other hand, in XML nodes tags may (and
 frequently do) occur repeatedly. If an XML document contains several nodes
 with the same tag, then the applications usually knows how to interpret the
 order in which the tags occur, but this order may not be detectable at the XML
 level (i.e. the nodes may not only have the same tag names, but also the same
 attributes and attribute values).

 The applications that use the XML document frequently require that the order
 of XML nodes with the same name remain intact when the document is modified.
 For example, the entries of a telephone book may be sorted alphabetically
 without XML being aware of that. Reading, modifying, and writing back the
 data in the telephone book must therefore not destroy that order.

@item Likewise, at least for readability reasons, the order of node
 attributes should not be changed. XML documents are frequently processed
 with text tools like @b{diff} which would incorrectly show differences
 between XML documents that are equivalent from an XML perspective.

@item Conflicts between tag names and attribute names. In XML, the same name
  can designate an attribute in one node and a tag in another node. тОХXML keeps
  all information from the < of a start tag to the > of an end tag in a single
  associative array, therefore the attribute names must somehow differ from
  the (sub-) tag names.

@item Every XML node has a tag name that can be used to derive a
  corresponding APL member name. However, the text segments between an XML
  tag and its corresponding end tag, are a mixture of unstructured text, XML
  subnodes and comments of which only the XML subnodes have tags of their own.
  These untagged segments may, however, contain relevant information and,
  from an XML standard perspective, both their content and their order must
  be preserved.
@end itemize

тОХXML solves these issues with a simple naming convention for all member names
in the (recursive) associative array that is produced by monadic тОХXML. Every
member name consists of 3 components that together yield a valid APL variable
name (and therefore a valid member name that is understood by the APL parser):

@itemize
@item A single character тНЩ, тИЖ, or _, that indicates the role of the name in
  the XML document as follows:
  @itemize
  @item the character тНЩ characterizes an attribute name, i.e. a name that
  was used @b{inside} (i.e. between < and >) of an XML start or leaf tag.
  The character тНЩ alone is the name of a special member which is present
  in every associative array below the top-level and whose value is the
  original XML tag name of a tag, or

  @item the character тИЖ characterizes a name that was synthesized by тОХXML
  itself to tag a text (sub-) segment that has no tag of its own. The
  corresponding XML entity was not a tag (and therefore had no tag name), or

  @item the character _ characterizes the name of an XML entity, i.e. a CML
  name that occurred @b{between} the start tag and the corresponding end tag
  (if any: leaf tags have no such entities)
  @end itemize

@item a position prefix of the form @b{NN}, where NN is the position
 of the member in relation to the tag to which it belongs. The numbering
 starts at тОХIO and restarts at every XML start or leaf tag.

@item the attribute name or tag name. For those parts of an XML entity that
  do not have a tag name, the member name is synthesized by тОХXML and the
  member value will be the text in the XML document with predefined XML
  entities replaced by their single characters, i.e.:
  @itemize
  @item & for &amp,
  @item < for &lt,
  @item > for &gt,
  @item ' for &apos,
  @item " for &quot,
  @item тОХUCS nnn for &#nnn, and
  @item тОХUCS $xxx for &#xxx
  @end itemize
@end itemize

Let NN be a sequence of decimal digits. Then only the following 4
synthesized names are produced by тОХXML:

@itemize
@item @b{тИЖNNcomment} for XML comments, i.e. <!--- ... ---> in XML,
@item @b{тИЖNNdeclaration} for XML declarations, i.e. <? ... ?> in XML,
@item @b{тИЖNNdoctype} for document type declarations, i.e.
    <!DOCTYPE ... > in XML
@item @b{тИЖNNtext} for unstructured (and hence untagged) text segements in XML.
@end itemize

Every XML name (of a tag or attribute) is also a valid APL name, but
valid APL names may also contain the characters _, тИЖ, and тНЩ which are not
valid in XML and used in the naming convention above to clearly separate
the member names used in APL from the names used in the XML document.

The essence of all this is that @b{everything} that belongs to an XML
node or document, i.e. the attributes inside a tag, the sub-nodes between a
start tag and its corresponding end tag (if any), declarations, etc. will
be contained in a single associative array.

Examples of APL member names (assuming тОХIOтЖР1):

@verbatim
      тНЩ1              тНЭ the first member in every XML node. Its value is the node tag.
      тИЖ1declaration   тНЭ the first member in most XML documents. E.g. <?xml version= ...>
      тИЖ2text          тНЭ whitespace (LF) between _1тИЖdeclaration and _3тИЖdoctype
      тИЖ3doctype       тНЭ DTD in XML documents that have one. E.g. <!DOCTYPE  ...
      _6Workspace     тНЭ Sub-array for <Workspace ... at position 6.
      тНЩ1wsid          тНЭ first attribute wsid from e.g. <Workspace wsid=...
      тНЩ2year          тНЭ second attribute year
@end verbatim

@subsection Monadic тОХXML

@b{Z тЖР тОХXML B} converts APL string B that contains a valid XML document
to an associative APL array Z and vice versa.

@b{Note}: If you convert an associative APL array back to a an XML document,
the result is a possibly very long string containing several linefeed
characters. That is OK if the string is written to a file, but causes problems
when the string is displayed and longer than тОХPW. The standard APL
folding of output near тОХPW make the string then look somewhat garbled.
This effect can be suppressed in 2 ways:

@enumerate
@item set тОХPW large enough, or
@item prefix the string with тКГ35тОХCR as in the examples below.
@end enumerate

