@node    Section 2.41
@section Conditionals

@b{WARNING}: GNU APL conditionals are experimental. Use them with care and
avoid them, wherever possible, in favour of portability. Neither the ISO
APL standard, nor IBM APL2 provide conditionals.

@subsection Design considerations.

The author of GNU APL has, for a long time, hesitated to implement
conditionals in GNU APL. Primarily for the following reasons:

@itemize
@item the lack of standardization of conditionals,
@item the lack of an elegant syntax that fits well into the typical
      (brief) APL programming style, and in particular
@item the large number of keywords for flow control used in some other APL
      interpreters. See below.
@end itemize

The C language has six keywords for flow control: @b{if} @b{else}, @b{for},
@b{while}, @b{do}, @b{switch} and @b{goto}. Two of them (@b{do} and @b{while})
are redundant and rarely used, leaving only 4 base cases. A quick @b{grep -c}
over the 100,000 top-level C++ source code lines of GNU APL reveals the
following statistics:

@itemize
  @item 7000 @b{if} statements, 1600 of them two-sided if-then-else-endif,
  the others one-sided if-then-endif,
  @item 2000 @b{for} statements, 1200 of them trivial iterations over some
  array (aka. @i{for (int i = 0; i < size; ++i) ... },
  @item 200 @b{switch} statements with an averge of 8 case clauses per switch,
  @item 250 @b{while} statements, and
  @item 70 @b{do while} statements
@end itemize

In contrast, a popular non-free APL interpreter came up with a zoo of 30
or so keywords for the purpose of flow control in one way or another:

:If :While :Repeat :For :In :InEach :Select :With :Trap :Hold :Disposable
:Else :ElseIf :AndIf :OrIf :Until :Case :CaseList :EndIf :EndWhile :EndRepeat
:EndFor :EndSelect :EndWith :EndTrap :EndHold :EndDisposable
:GoTo, :Return, :Leave :Continue

This approach, its implementation, and its constraints raise a number of
serious problems. To name a few:

@itemize
  @item A rather common APL design practice is to first debug non-trivial
  APL statements in immediate execution mode and only transfer them into
  the body of defined functions when they work properly. However, the keywords 
  above seem to work only in the bodies of defined functions but @b{not} in
  immediate execution mode. The reason seems to be that their implementation
  depends on labels which are not available in immediate execution.

  @item Another rather common design practice is to limit the length of
  lines to less than 80 characters (e.g. in the GNU coding conventions,
  @b{https://gcc.gnu.org/codingconventions.html#Line}).
  Even if it were possible to squeeze an :If :Then :Else :Endif into an 80
  character line, and using a single whitespace around the keywords for
  readability, wastes almost 1/3 of the precious 80 characters for keywords.
  In this example, each of the COND, THEN, and ELSE parts must then be < 20
  characters on average. Not to talk about indentation to clarify the code.

  @item Each of the keywords has rather specific constraints as to how and
  where it can be used. For example (to quote a simple one from a reference
  manual):

  @i{Control words, including qualifiers such as :Else and :ElseIf, may occur
  only at the beginning of a line or expression in a diamond-separated
  statement. The only exceptions are :In and :InEach which must appear on
  the same line within a :For expression.}

  These constraints suggest that the keywords mentioned are merely syntactic
  sugar that covers the underlying APL structure, i.e. labels and computed
  branches. GNU APL does not claim to be fundamentally different in that
  regard, but the syntax of the syntactic sugar is somewhat simpler.
@end itemize

Learning from the above, the conclusions for the syntax of GNU APL condionals
were these:

@enumerate
  @item the syntax shall be easy to understand and consistent,
  @item the syntax shall work in immediate execution mode (as long as
  the entire conditional is provided on a single input line),
  @item to support 2., lengthy keywords shall be avoided in favour of the
  original APL style, and
  @item the syntax needs to only support those cases where the standard APL
  flow control (i.e. тЖТN) becomes cumbersome. There is absolutely no benefit in
  introducing a new (and redundant) syntax when the standard APL mechanism
  is already completely adequate.
@end enumerate

As to the last point, almost every flow control case (in a standards compliant
APL program) falls into one of the following categories (sorted by
increasing complexity):

@enumerate
@item @b{one-sided if}: if COND then THEN endif
@item @b{two-sided if/else}: if COND then THEN else ELSE endif
@item @b{loop}: while COND do BODY (or its less frequently used twin do BODY
while COND)
@item @b{switch/case}: switch ARG case CASE1 case CASE2 case ... CASEn endswitch
@end enumerate

where THEN, ELSE, CASE1, CASE2, CASEn, and BODY are a sequence of one or more
statements, while COND or ARG control which of these sequences (if any)
shall be executed.

Interestingly, the complexity of the above cases, when coded in APL,
increases in amost the reverse order (compared to other languages).
For example,

@enumerate
@item @b{switch/case}:
@verbatim
    тЖТ(ARG) / L1  L2 ...  Ln   тНЭ switch(ARG)
L1: CASE1 тЧК тЖТL_endcase        тНЭ case 1:
L2: CASE2 тЧК тЖТL_endcase        тНЭ case 2:
...
LN: CASEn                     тНЭ case N:
L_endcase:
@end verbatim

@item @b{loop}:
@verbatim
 Loop: BODY тЧК тЖТ(COND) / Loop   тНЭ repeat BODY while COND
@end verbatim

@item @b{one-sided if}:
@verbatim
  тЖТ(!COND) / L_endif   тНЭ jump over the THEN clause
  THEN
L_endif:
@end verbatim

or, not uncommon and shorter, but less portable and less readable:

@verbatim
  тЖТ(!COND) / тЖС1+тОХLC тЧК THEN  тНЭ jump over the THEN clause to the next line
@end verbatim

@item @b{two-sided if/else}:
@verbatim
  тЖТCOND тЖУ L_else L_then
L_then: THEN тЧК тЖТL_endif
L_else: ELSE
L_endif:
@end verbatim
@end enumerate

A closer look at these cases reveals that there is not much room for
syntax improvements in cases 1. (switch) and 2. (loop). The introduction of
a new syntax like :Select / :Case for switches or :For / :Endfor for loops
would therefore only make matters different and incompatible, but not better.

In case 3. (one-sided if) there is also not much to gain. However, case 3. 
can be seen as a special case of case 4. (with an empty ELSE clause). As
a matter of consistency, a new syntax for case 4. should also cover case 3.

The only cases where a new syntax could improve matters are therefore
cases 3. and  4.

Another consideration relates to the end marker @b{L_endif} (and would
likewise relate to @b{L_endcase} if we hadn't already ruled that case out).
There are two reasonable syntax alternatives to handle the branch to the
end of the conditional:

@enumerate
@item allow multiple statements in the THEN and ELSE clauses and mark the end
  of the @b{ELSE} clause (or, in the one-sided case 3 of the @b{THEN} clause
  with some @b{ENDIF} marker, or
@item allow only single statement clauses (which implies the @b{ENDIF} and
 makes it obsolete.
@end enumerate

The design decision made in GNU APL was to go for multiple statements because
the advantage in 2. (shorter code) looks much smaller than the advantages
of 1. (e.g. insertion of debug printouts into a clause).

@subsection Syntax

With the above considerations in mind, GNU APL decided for the following
syntax:

@itemize
@item @b{one-sided if/else}:
@verbatim
      COND тЖТтЖТ THEN тЖРтЖР
@end verbatim

@item @b{two-sided if/else}:
@verbatim
      COND тЖТтЖТ THEN тЖРтЖТ ELSE тЖРтЖР
@end verbatim

@end itemize

For this syntax to work, the following rules must be followed:

@itemize
  @item The тЖТтЖТ, тЖРтЖТ, and тЖРтЖР markers must be single tokens (2 adjacent Unicode
  characters) That is, no whitespace (and in particular no line feed) is
  permitted between the first and the second arrow. A single тЖТ is a valid
  APL statement (named Escape). A linefeed between two тЖТ turns the single
  token тЖТтЖТ into two valid (though most of the time useless) Escape statements.

  @item The тЖТтЖТ, тЖРтЖТ, and тЖРтЖР tokens are @b{end-of statement} markers (as opposed
  to @b{beginning-of statement} markers). Each marker binds to the non-empty
  statement left of it. APL is parsed line by line, so there can never be a
  valid non-empty APL statement left of the first token of a line. As a
  consequence, a тЖТтЖТ token, a тЖРтЖТ token, or a тЖРтЖР token at the beginning of
  a line is a SYNTAX ERROR.

  @item The COND, THEN, and ELSE clauses shall be non-empty (!) sequences of
  valid APL statements. In particular:
  @itemize

  @item The condition COND shall be a @i{single statement} that evaluates to
  a 1-item Boolean array (of any rank). The statement result of COND is a
  committed value (and therefore not displayed).

  @item The THEN clause shall be @i{one or more valid statements}, separated
  by тЧК for more than one statement.

  @item The ELSE clause (if present) shall be @i{one or more valid statements},
  separated by тЧК for more than one statement.
  @end itemize
@end itemize

Examples:
@verbatim
      тНЭ short format. Valid in immediate execution and in defined functions
      тНЭ
      XтЖР5 тЧК XтЙе0 тЖТтЖТ X 'is positive' тЖРтЖТ X 'is negative' тЖРтЖР
 5 is positive 


      тНЭ long format. Only possible in defined functions because immediate
      тНЭ execution works line by line (and parsing the first line would fail).

      тНЭ valid split into several lines (in a defined function)
      тНЭ
      тИЗFOO X
       XтЙе0             тЖТтЖТ
       X 'is positive' тЖРтЖТ
       X 'is negative' тЖРтЖР
      тИЗ
      FOO 5
 5 is positive 
      FOO ┬п5
 ┬п5 is negative 


      тНЭ invalid split into several lines: тЖРтЖТ spread over 2 lines.
      тНЭ FOO can be properly parsed, but calling FOO fails.
      тНЭ
      тИЗFOO X
      XтЙе0 тЖТтЖТ X 'is positive' тЖР
           тЖТ X 'is negative' тЖРтЖР
      тИЗ
      FOO 5
SYNTAX ERROR
FOO[1]  X 'is positive'тЖР


      тНЭ invalid split into several lines: тЖРтЖТ is first token in line).
      тНЭ FOO is invalid and the тИЗ-editor complains when closing FOO.
      тНЭ
      тИЗFOO X
       XтЙе0 тЖТтЖТ X 'is positive'
           тЖРтЖТ X 'is negative' тЖРтЖР
      тИЗ
NOTE: Invalid тЖРтЖТ at start of line 2
Error in function body in function line [2] of:
[0] FOO X
[1]        XтЙе0 тЖТтЖТ X 'is positive'
[2]            тЖРтЖТ X 'is negative' тЖРтЖР
Fatal error in defined function line [2]. You may now:
    change the faulty line  with:  [2] ..., or 
    delete the faulty line  with:  [тИЖ2], or
    cancel editing with:  [тЖТ]тИЗ.

@end verbatim

The recommended usage of corresponding тЖТтЖТ, тЖРтЖТ, and тЖРтЖР token is to:

@itemize
  @item either put them on the same line (short format), or else
  @item align all of them on the same column (long form), but
  @item never mix the short and long forms
@end itemize

Like shown in the examples above.

