@node    Section 2.42
@section Matrix Product

In standard APL, the inner product Z of two matrices A and B as known from
linear algebra, is:

@verbatim
      ZтЖРA +.├Ч B      тНЭ the most frequent special case of A f.g B
@end verbatim

However, the inner product in APL is more generic than the inner product in
linear algebra. In the general case @b{A f.g B} may the functions @b{f}
and @b{g} also be non-scalar APL primitives or even defined functions.
This generality is occasionally helpful, but comes with a performance
penalty since many argument checks are duplicated. At the same time
@b{A +.├Ч B} is by far the most frequent use of operator '.'.

For this reason GNU APL also provides a more efficient dyadic function
@b{тИШ} (Matrix Product) for the special case @b{+.├Ч} of the dyadic
operator '.'. This function тИШ has been optimized for numeric arguments
and computes the matrix product as known from linear algebra.

For two-dimensional matrices A and B function тИШ is the same as +.├Ч:

AтИШB тЖРтЖТ A +.├Ч B

Otherwise there are some subtle differences between тИШ and +.├Ч:

@itemize
@item @b{A +.├Ч B} allows A and B to be of any rank, while @b{AтИШB} raises a
 RANK ERROR if the rank of A or B is more than 2.
@item With operator +.├Ч the product of e.g. a vector and a matrix (or
 vice versa) is a vector, usually understood as row-vector.
 In contrast (and more similar to linear algebra) AтИШB is always a matrix,
 to preserve the distinction between row vectors and column vectors:

@verbatim
      MтЖР2 2тН┤1 2 3 4   тНЭ a matrix
      VтЖР10 11         тНЭ a vector

      M +.├Ч V
32 74

      MтИШV
32
74

      V +.├Ч M
43 64

      VтИШM
43 64

      тН┤M +.├Ч V   тНЭ vector
2
      тН┤V +.├Ч M   тНЭ vector
2
      тН┤VтИШM       тНЭ row vector
1 2
      тН┤MтИШV       тНЭ column vector
2 1
@end verbatim
@end itemize

